          "content": "No — we don't track the provenance of the content itself. We have `source_message_ids` (which original messages it came from) but nothing that says \"this `content_en` is a direct user statement vs a translation vs an agent-derived compaction\".\n\nThat's a gap. Right now a compacted/merged memory looks identical to a direct user quote in the schema. You can't tell if `content_en` is:\n- The user's own English words (verbatim)\n- KP's translation from Hungarian\n- KP's compaction/summary of multiple messages\n- A merge of two extracted memories\n\nThis could be a simple `origin` or `integrity` enum field:\n\n| Value | Meaning | Trust implication |\n|-------|---------|-------------------|\n| `verbatim` | User's exact words, unmodified | Highest — ground truth |\n| `translated` | KP translated from original language | High — but check `content_original` if ambiguous |\n| `extracted` | KP extracted/summarized from conversation | Medium — interpretation, may lose nuance |\n| `compacted` | KP merged/compressed multiple memories | Lower — derived, further from source |\n\nWant me to add this to the trust spec as a companion field? It ties directly into trust — you can't properly score reliability without knowing how far the content is from the original utterance."
        }
      },
