        "content": {
          "Prompt": {
            "prompt": "so let's broden: how about a complete extended CIA triad, what makes sense here - I guess Availibility is not in case of memories, if not found it is not aval"
          }
        },
        "timestamp": "2026-03-20T09:57:01.489016286+01:00",
        "images": null
      },
      "assistant": {
        "ToolUse": {
          "message_id": "54dee385-ddac-4aa8-8331-1bac9f71e4ad",
          "content": "",
          "tool_uses": [
            {
              "id": "tooluse_uMFP7U9FuNvssDtPXaTO0N",
              "name": "thinking",
              "orig_name": "thinking",
              "args": {
                "thought": "The CIA triad: Confidentiality, Integrity, Availability. Let me think about how each maps to the memory system.\n\n**Confidentiality** — already done: classification (0-3). Who can see this memory.\n\n**Integrity** — how trustworthy/accurate is this memory. This is what we're building now with trust + origin. But integrity in the CIA sense is broader:\n- Source trust (owner/self/peer/untrusted) — who provided it\n- Origin/provenance (verbatim/translated/extracted/compacted) — how far from ground truth\n- Tamper detection — has it been modified since creation? (not currently tracked)\n- Freshness — is it still current/valid?\n\n**Availability** — the user is right that this is less relevant for memories. If a memory isn't found by search, it's \"unavailable\" but that's a search quality issue, not a security property. However:\n- Recall cascade stages are about availability — ensuring memories CAN be found\n- The archive DB future idea is about availability — moving old memories to cold storage\n- Backup (chat_backup table) is availability\n- But these are operational concerns, not per-memory metadata\n\nSo for per-memory fields, we really have two useful axes:\n1. **Confidentiality** = classification (done)\n2. **Integrity** = trust (source reliability) + origin (provenance) \n\nAvailability doesn't need a per-memory field — it's a system-level property.\n\nThe \"extended CIA triad\" sometimes includes:\n- Authentication (who created it) — partially covered by trust/source\n- Authorization (who can access) — covered by classification\n- Non-repudiation (proof of origin) — source_message_ids partially covers this\n- Accountability (audit trail) — sleep audit logs\n\nLet me lay this out clearly for the user.\n"
              },
              "orig_args": {
                "thought": "The CIA triad: Confidentiality, Integrity, Availability. Let me think about how each maps to the memory system.\n\n**Confidentiality** — already done: classification (0-3). Who can see this memory.\n\n**Integrity** — how trustworthy/accurate is this memory. This is what we're building now with trust + origin. But integrity in the CIA sense is broader:\n- Source trust (owner/self/peer/untrusted) — who provided it\n- Origin/provenance (verbatim/translated/extracted/compacted) — how far from ground truth\n- Tamper detection — has it been modified since creation? (not currently tracked)\n- Freshness — is it still current/valid?\n\n**Availability** — the user is right that this is less relevant for memories. If a memory isn't found by search, it's \"unavailable\" but that's a search quality issue, not a security property. However:\n- Recall cascade stages are about availability — ensuring memories CAN be found\n- The archive DB future idea is about availability — moving old memories to cold storage\n- Backup (chat_backup table) is availability\n- But these are operational concerns, not per-memory metadata\n\nSo for per-memory fields, we really have two useful axes:\n1. **Confidentiality** = classification (done)\n2. **Integrity** = trust (source reliability) + origin (provenance) \n\nAvailability doesn't need a per-memory field — it's a system-level property.\n\nThe \"extended CIA triad\" sometimes includes:\n- Authentication (who created it) — partially covered by trust/source\n- Authorization (who can access) — covered by classification\n- Non-repudiation (proof of origin) — source_message_ids partially covers this\n- Accountability (audit trail) — sleep audit logs\n\nLet me lay this out clearly for the user.\n"
              }
            }
          ]
        }
