        "Response": {
          "message_id": "4700b422-b03b-4114-ad48-37b2815545cb",
          "content": "Here's what I found:\n\nYou're onto something that the industry is just starting to formalize. Three major sources confirm this:\n\n**1. SuperLocalMemory (arxiv, Feb 2026)** — the closest to what you're building. It's a local-first SQLite+FTS5 memory system (sound familiar?) with a Bayesian trust scoring framework. Every memory records four provenance fields: `created_by`, `source_protocol`, `trust_score` at write time, and `provenance_chain` (full modification history). They use Beta-Binomial posterior inference for trust — agents start at trust=1.0 and trust is asymmetric (harder to gain than lose). They specifically defend against OWASP ASI06 (memory poisoning). [Source](https://arxiv.org/html/2603.02240v1)\n\n**2. Sakura Sky — \"Secure Memory Governance\" (Nov 2025)** — a 17-part series on trustworthy AI agents. Part 14 is exactly about memory governance. They define 7 primitives including memory layer classification, access control with trust domains, memory poisoning detection with provenance at insertion time, and compartmentalization by trust tier. Their key insight: \"memory is a security boundary, not an implementation detail.\" [Source](https://www.sakurasky.com/blog/missing-primitives-for-trustworthy-ai-part-14/)\n\n**3. OWASP ASI06 (2025)** — memory and context poisoning is now in the OWASP Top 10 for Agentic AI. This is the formal threat model that both papers reference.\n\n**What nobody is doing yet** (your edge):\n- The CIA triad mapped to per-memory fields (classification + trust + integrity as three queryable columns) — SuperLocalMemory has trust but no confidentiality classification or integrity/provenance enum\n- The `integrity` field tracking verbatim→translated→extracted→compacted provenance chain — nobody has this\n- The interaction matrix (trust never overrides classification) — not formalized anywhere\n\nThe military angle: Multi-Level Security (MLS) systems like Bell-LaPadula have done classification + clearance levels for decades, but applied to *documents*, not to AI agent memories. You're essentially applying MLS principles to the memory layer of an autonomous agent — that's novel.\n\nWant me to add these references to the spec?\n\nContent was rephrased for compliance with licensing restrictions.\n\nReferences:\n[1] SuperLocalMemory: Privacy-Preserving Multi-Agent Memory with Bayesian Trust Defense - https://arxiv.org/html/2603.02240v1\n[2] Trustworthy AI Agents: Secure Memory Governance - Sakura Sky - https://www.sakurasky.com/blog/missing-primitives-for-trustworthy-ai-part-14/\n[3] AI agent memory poisoning: how attackers corrupt Long-Term agent behavior - https://www.mintmcp.com/blog/ai-agent-memory-poisoning\n[4] The Role of Memory Provenance in AI Risk Management - https://memvid.com/blog/the-role-of-memory-provenance-in-ai-risk-management"
        }
      },
