    "Now let me check if the fix was ever applied to the actual files:\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "\n[Tool uses: thinking]",
    "Here's the summary:\n\n---\n\n## Error Chat Summary\n\n### What happened\nA 54-turn chat session investigating and planning a fix for two bugs. The session crashed/was interrupted at the very last step (Turn 53) when the assistant attempted to implement the fix — it issued an `execute_bash` tool call with **empty input `{}`**, and the conversation ended with `next_message: None`. Neither fix was applied.\n\n### Last step where it failed\n**Turn 53** — User said \"Implement this plan\" with the full fix spec. The assistant's first tool call had empty parameters and the session died. No code was changed.\n\n### The two bugs that need to be fixed\n\n**Bug 1: Sleep process never exits**\n- File: `src/cli/agentbridge-sleep.ts` (line 399-403)\n- Problem: `main()` resolves successfully but Node.js stays alive because of lingering handles (unix sockets from ACP ndjson stream / better-sqlite3). There's only a `.catch()` handler — no `.then()` to call `process.exit(0)`.\n- Effect: Sleep processes stack up indefinitely. The bridge's `sleepChild` reference is never cleared, so the bridge thinks it's perpetually sleeping and queues all incoming messages forever.\n- Fix: Add `.then(() => process.exit(0))` to the `main()` call:\n```typescript\nif (isDirectRun) {\n  main()\n    .then(() => process.exit(0))\n    .catch((err) => {\n      process.stderr.write(`Fatal: ${err instanceof Error ? err.message : String(err)}\\n`);\n      process.exit(1);\n    });\n}\n```\n\n**Bug 2: Queued messages from same chat collide on `busyChats`**\n- File: `src/main.ts` — `processPendingMessages()` function (line 271-297)\n- Problem: When the sleep process finally exits (or is killed), `processPendingMessages()` injects all queued messages via `injectUpdate()` in a tight loop. Message 1 adds the sessionKey to `busyChats`. Messages 2+ from the same chat immediately hit the `busyChats` guard → user gets \"⏳ Previous request still in progress...\" → those messages are effectively lost.\n- Fix: Before injecting, group queued messages by sessionKey, concatenate their texts with `\\n\\n`, and inject one synthetic update per chat instead of one per message.\n\n### Current code state\nBoth files are **unfixed** — the code is exactly as it was before the implementation attempt.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> fix the 2 bugs",
    "\n[Tool uses: fs_write]",
    "Now Bug 2 — let me see the exact current `processPendingMessages` to write a precise replacement:\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "Let me check the type of `pendingMessages` to understand the shape:\n[Tool uses: grep]",
    "\n[Tool uses: fs_write]",
    "Now build and test:\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "Strict null checks. The `Map.values()` group is always non-empty since we only set it with at least one element, but TS doesn't know that. Quick fix:\n[Tool uses: fs_write]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "Clean build. Now tests:\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "All 600 tests pass, clean build. Both bugs fixed:\n\n1. `src/cli/agentbridge-sleep.ts` — Added `.then(() => process.exit(0))` so the sleep process exits after `main()` completes instead of hanging forever on lingering handles.\n\n2. `src/main.ts` — `processPendingMessages()` now groups queued messages by `sessionKey` and merges them into one synthetic update per chat (texts joined with `\\n\\n`). This prevents messages 2+ from the same chat hitting the `busyChats` guard and getting the \"⏳ Previous request still in progress...\" rejection.\n[Tool uses: none]",
