    "Now let me check how the sleep prompt loader works:\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "Good, I have the full picture. Here's the plan:\n\n---\n\n**Implementation Plan — Browser Subagent**\n\n**Problem Statement:**\nWhen the professor agent runs browser commands directly (via `execute_bash`), long-running or hanging browser operations block the entire bridge — no messages processed, no heartbeat, nothing. The X/Twitter cookie injection hung for 12+ minutes and froze KP completely.\n\n**Requirements:**\n- Browser tasks must run in a separate process so the main agent stays responsive\n- Follow the same subagent pattern as the sleep agent (spawn detached kiro-cli ACP process)\n- The professor should never run browser commands directly — always delegate to the browser subagent\n- Results should be reported back to the chat when the subagent finishes\n- A timeout should kill the subagent if it hangs too long\n\n**Proposed Solution:**\nCreate `agentbridge-browse` CLI that spawns a detached kiro-cli ACP subprocess with browser-specific steering. The professor calls this CLI (returns immediately), stays free for messages, and the bridge delivers the result when the subagent exits.\n\n```\nProfessor: \"I'll check your X notifications\"\n  → execute_bash: agentbridge-browse --task \"check X notifications\" --chat-id 123\n  → returns immediately: { \"ok\": true, \"taskId\": \"a1b2c3\", \"status\": \"spawned\" }\n  → Professor is FREE\n\nBackground (detached):\n  → kiro-cli acp --agent browser-agent\n  → does the work (navigate, screenshot, extract, etc.)\n  → writes result to ~/.agentbridge/memory/pending_results.json\n  → Bridge picks it up next cron tick → sends to chat\n```\n\n**Task Breakdown:**\n\nTask 1: Create `browsing_prompt.md` template\n- Objective: Template file that instructs the browser subagent what to do, similar to `sleeping_prompt.md`\n- Template variables: `${TASK}`, `${CHAT_ID}`, `${TIMESTAMP}`, `${BROWSER_STATUS}` (container running/not)\n- Sections: task description, available browser commands (from existing browser SKILL.md), docker container instructions, output format requirements\n- The prompt tells the subagent to use `agentbridge-browser` CLI for all browser actions and write a summary when done\n- File: `persona/browsing_prompt.md`\n- Demo: `cat persona/browsing_prompt.md` shows a complete template with variable placeholders\n\nTask 2: Create `agentbridge-browse` CLI\n- Objective: Thin launcher that builds the prompt, spawns a detached kiro-cli ACP subprocess, and returns immediately\n- Parse args: `--task` (required), `--chat-id` (required), `--timeout` (optional, default 5min), `--dry-run`\n- Build prompt from `browsing_prompt.md` template (same loader pattern as sleep-prompt-loader)\n- Spawn `kiro-cli acp --agent professor` detached with stdio piped to a log file at `~/.agentbridge/logs/browse_<taskId>.log`\n- Write task metadata to `~/.agentbridge/memory/pending_browse.json` (taskId, chatId, pid, startedAt, timeoutMs)\n- Print `{ \"ok\": true, \"taskId\": \"...\", \"status\": \"spawned\" }` and exit immediately\n- File: `src/cli/agentbridge-browse.ts`\n- Test: verify it returns immediately, writes pending_browse.json, doesn't block\n- Demo: `agentbridge-browse --task \"check X\" --chat-id 123 --dry-run` prints the prompt\n\nTask 3: Create browse result delivery + timeout watchdog in main.ts\n- Objective: Pick up completed/timed-out browse tasks and deliver results to chat\n- In the existing cron checker interval (5-min), also check `pending_browse.json`:\n  - For each entry: check if pid is still alive (`kill(pid, 0)`)\n  - If dead: read the log file, extract last 500 chars as result, write to `pending_reminders.json` with `🌐 Browse task completed: <task>\\n\\n<result>`, remove from pending_browse.json\n  - If alive but past timeout: kill the pid, report timeout\n- File: modify `src/components/cron-checker.ts` to add `checkBrowseTasks()`, wire in main.ts\n- Demo: spawn a browse task, wait for it to finish, result appears in chat\n\nTask 4: Update browser skill steering for professor\n- Objective: Modify the professor's browser skill to say \"always use `agentbridge-browse` for browser tasks, never run browser commands directly\"\n- Create `skills/browse-delegate/SKILL.md` — tells professor to delegate all browser work to `agentbridge-browse`\n- Keep existing `skills/browser/SKILL.md` unchanged (the browser subagent will use it)\n- Deploy the new skill in `scripts/deploy.sh`\n- Demo: professor's steering includes the delegation instruction\n\nTask 5: Deploy wiring + tests\n- Objective: Wire `agentbridge-browse` into deploy.sh, add tests\n- Add CLI wrapper + symlink in deploy.sh (same pattern as todo/cron)\n- Add `browsing_prompt.md` to deploy.sh\n- Add skill steering to deploy.sh\n- Tests for `agentbridge-browse`: arg parsing, dry-run mode, pending_browse.json write\n- Tests for browse task checking: pid dead → result delivered, timeout → killed\n- Demo: `./scripts/deploy.sh` deploys everything, full test suite passes\n\nDoes this plan look good, or would you like me to adjust anything?\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> don;t forget to creat e new tests",
    "\n\nTests are already in Task 5:\n\n> - Tests for `agentbridge-browse`: arg parsing, dry-run mode, pending_browse.json write\n> - Tests for browse task checking: pid dead → result delivered, timeout → killed\n\nBut let me make it more explicit — I'll split tests into their own task so they don't get skipped:\n\n**Updated Task 5: Tests**\n- `src/cli/agentbridge-browse.test.ts` — arg parsing (missing --task, missing --chat-id, valid args), dry-run prints prompt, spawns and writes pending_browse.json, returns immediately\n- `src/components/browse-checker.test.ts` — dead pid delivers result, timed-out pid gets killed, still-alive pid is left alone, missing log file handled gracefully\n\n**Updated Task 6: Deploy wiring**\n- CLI wrapper + symlink in deploy.sh\n- `browsing_prompt.md` deployment\n- Skill steering deployment\n- Full build + full test suite green\n\nDoes the plan look good now, or anything else to adjust?\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> question, need your professioonal advise as system architect: we mainly use the agent browser for complex task, like research on X, or write  apost on FB (later).. should we call it a Research Agent and also pass him what to research? Or the subagent Browser Agent just browsing and passes back the info to the main agent? ",
    "\n\nThis is a key architectural decision. Let me lay out both options:\n\n**Option A: Dumb Browser Agent** — just browses, returns raw data\n```\nProfessor: \"check my X notifications\"\n  → spawns Browser Agent: \"navigate to x.com/notifications, extract text, screenshot\"\n  → Browser Agent returns: raw page text + screenshot\n  → Professor interprets the results, decides what to tell user\n```\n\n**Option B: Smart Research Agent** — understands the goal, drives the browser autonomously\n```\nProfessor: \"check my X notifications\"\n  → spawns Research Agent: \"check X notifications, summarize what's new\"\n  → Research Agent: navigates, scrolls, extracts, takes screenshots, reasons about what it sees\n  → Research Agent returns: \"You have 3 new mentions: @alice replied to your thread about...\"\n```\n\nMy recommendation: **Option B — Research Agent**, for these reasons:\n\n1. **Browser tasks are multi-step and require judgment.** Logging into X, handling cookie injection, navigating to the right page, scrolling, deciding what's relevant — this isn't a \"fetch URL, return text\" job. The agent needs to react to what it sees (login wall? captcha? empty feed? error page?).\n\n2. **Round-trips kill you.** If the Browser Agent is dumb, the professor has to orchestrate every step: \"navigate here\" → wait → \"what do you see?\" → wait → \"click that\" → wait. Each round-trip goes through the bridge. With a smart agent, it does 10 browser actions autonomously and comes back with a summary.\n\n3. **The sleep agent is the proof.** The sleep agent isn't a \"dumb file reader\" — it gets a high-level goal (\"do overnight maintenance\") and autonomously decides what to consolidate, what to clean, what to skip. Same pattern works here.\n\n4. **Future tasks confirm this.** Writing a Facebook post, researching a topic, checking notifications — these are all goal-oriented, not step-oriented. You want to say \"post this on FB\" not \"navigate to fb.com, click compose, fill text, click post.\"\n\n**How I'd structure it:**\n\n```\nagentbridge-browse --task \"Check my X/Twitter notifications and summarize\" --chat-id 123\n```\n\nThe `browsing_prompt.md` template would include:\n- The task goal (from `--task`)\n- All browser tool instructions (from existing browser SKILL.md)\n- Docker container setup instructions\n- Cookie/auth state info\n- Output format: \"write a concise summary of what you found/did\"\n\nThe Research Agent is a full kiro-cli with tool access — it can browse, take screenshots, reason, retry on errors, and come back with an intelligent summary. Not just raw HTML dumps.\n\nOne nuance: I'd still call it **Browser Agent** (not Research Agent), because it'll also handle non-research tasks like \"post on FB\" or \"fill out this form.\" \"Research\" is too narrow. The key distinction is: it's the agent that has browser access and autonomy to complete browser-based goals.\n\nWant me to update the plan with this direction?\n[Tool uses: none]",
