    "All 6 tasks already implemented and verified:\n\n- ✅ Task 1: `persona/browsing_prompt.md` — template with `${TASK}`, `${CHAT_ID}`, `${TIMESTAMP}`, `${BROWSER_STATUS}`\n- ✅ Task 2: `src/cli/agentbridge-browse.ts` — 181 lines, spawns detached kiro-cli, returns immediately\n- ✅ Task 3: `checkBrowseTasks()` in cron-checker + wired in main.ts (interval + startup)\n- ✅ Task 4: `skills/browse-delegate/SKILL.md` — tells professor to never run browser commands directly\n- ✅ Task 5: 13 new tests (8 browse CLI + 5 browse checker)\n- ✅ Task 6: deploy.sh wired (CLI wrapper, skill steering, prompt template)\n\nBuild clean, 61 test files, 633 tests all passing. I built it while we were discussing the plan.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> 1 more thing: the browser usage shoudl be headless",
    "\n\nThe browser is already headless by default — the `agentbridge-browser` CLI uses the headless Chromium in the Docker container. The headed mode only activates when you explicitly start the container with `--headed` flag (`browser-docker.sh --headed`).\n\nBut the issue that caused the hang was that KP ran a custom `docker exec` script that imported `BrowserManager` directly and launched a headed Chrome (`/opt/google/chrome/chrome` without `--headless`). The `browse-delegate` skill already prevents that — it tells the professor to NEVER run `docker exec` or `agentbridge-browser` directly, only `agentbridge-browse`.\n\nSo the fix is already in place. The Browser Agent will use `agentbridge-browser` which goes through the headless shell. Want me to also add an explicit note in the `browsing_prompt.md` template to reinforce \"always use headless, never launch headed browsers\"?\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> how can I or KiroProf check what is going on inside the headless browser?",
    "\n\nThe browser agent already has the tools — it just needs to use them:\n\n1. **Screenshot** — `agentbridge-browser --action screenshot --session-id browse` returns a base64 image. The agent can take one at any step to see what's on screen.\n\n2. **Extract text** — `agentbridge-browser --action extract_text --session-id browse` returns visible page text (up to 4000 chars). Scoped with `--selector` for specific elements.\n\n3. **Page info** — `agentbridge-browser --action get_page_info --session-id browse` lists all interactive elements (links, buttons, inputs) with their selectors. Shows the agent what it can click/fill.\n\nThese are already in the `browsing_prompt.md` template. The Browser Agent can screenshot after every navigation to \"see\" what happened, extract text to read content, and get_page_info to discover what's clickable.\n\nFor **you** to manually peek inside:\n\n```bash\n# Quick screenshot\nagentbridge-browser --action screenshot --session-id browse | jq -r '.screenshot' | base64 -d > /tmp/browser.png\n\n# What's on the page right now\nagentbridge-browser --action extract_text --session-id browse\n\n# What elements are available\nagentbridge-browser --action get_page_info --session-id browse\n\n# Check active sessions\ndocker exec agentbridge-browser ps aux | grep chrome\n```\n\nOr if you want a live view, start a second container with `--headed` for debugging — but the agent should always use headless.\n[Tool uses: none]",
