    "No agent needed — this is pure logic. Here's the design:\n\n**New file:** `~/.agentbridge/memory/cron_runs.json` — tracks last execution time per crontab command:\n```json\n{\n  \"ai-news-24h\": { \"lastRun\": 1773730800000, \"command\": \"agentbridge-browse --task ...\" }\n}\n```\n\n**New function:** `checkMissedCrons()` in `cron-checker.ts`:\n1. On startup, read `crontab -l`\n2. Parse each entry with `cron-parser` (tiny npm package) to get the previous scheduled fire time\n3. Compare with `lastRun` in `cron_runs.json`\n4. If previous fire time > lastRun (or no lastRun exists), execute the command now\n5. Update `lastRun`\n\n**Wiring:** called once on startup in `main.ts`, right after the existing `checkCron()` + `checkBrowseTasks()` startup calls.\n\nSo if the bridge was down at 8am, and you start it at 10am, it sees \"the 8am job should have run but didn't\" and fires it immediately.\n\nOne question: should ALL crontab entries be catch-up-able, or only ones with a marker? I'd suggest marking them with a comment like `# agentbridge-managed` so we don't accidentally re-run unrelated cron jobs. Like:\n\n```\n0 8 * * * /home/qakosal/.local/bin/agentbridge-browse --task \"...\" --chat-id 7773842843 --timeout 600 # agentbridge-managed\n```\n\nSound good?\n[Tool uses: none]",
