    "\n[Tool uses: thinking]",
    "Found the root cause. Sleep takes 1-3 min to complete and write the audit file. The heartbeat ticks every 30 min, but during that window there's no guard — it checks for audit files, finds none, spawns again. Multiple concurrent sleeps fight over the DB lock, crash silently (stdio:ignore), none write audit, cycle repeats.\n\nFix: add an in-memory spawn guard to `SleepTrigger`:\n[Tool uses: fs_write]",
    "> t",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "Clean. The fix:\n\n- `spawnedToday` flag in `SleepTrigger` — set to `true` on first spawn (startup or cron), blocks all subsequent attempts within the same bridge session\n- Combined with the existing audit file check, this covers both in-process concurrency (new flag) and cross-restart protection (audit files)\n\nThe 4 runs this morning happened because sleep was spawned, took 1-3 min, but the next heartbeat tick saw no audit file yet and spawned again. Now the first spawn sets the flag and all subsequent ticks get \"Already spawned today — skip\".\n\nNeeds a rebuild + restart of the bridge to take effect.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> also what is with the new app start trigger of sleeping? Does it check it is passed morning and it should be running or how it is setup now?",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "There it is — `shouldRunOnStartup()` always returns `true`. No time check, no audit check. Every bridge restart triggers a sleep, even if it already ran today.\n\nThat's the other half of the problem. The fix should be: on startup, only run sleep if it's past 8am AND no audit exists for today.\n[Tool uses: fs_write]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "Now the startup sleep logic is:\n\n- **Before 8am** → skip (no point running maintenance at 3am)\n- **≥8am + audit exists today** → skip (already ran)\n- **≥8am + no audit today** → run (missed the morning cycle, catch up)\n\nCombined with the `spawnedToday` guard on the cron path, sleep now runs exactly once per day max — whether triggered by startup or heartbeat, whichever comes first.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> I am just wondering, shouldn't we just relay on the heartbeat triggered cron or the startup is just a safety net?",
    "\n\nThe startup trigger is a safety net, and a useful one. Here's why:\n\nThe heartbeat cron requires **10 min idle** before it fires. If you restart the bridge at 9am and immediately start chatting, the heartbeat will keep seeing \"user active in last 10min\" and defer. If you stay active all day, sleep never runs.\n\nThe startup trigger bypasses the idle check — it fires once on boot if it's past 8am and sleep hasn't run today. So even if you're actively chatting, the morning maintenance still happens.\n\nWithout it, the only way sleep runs is: bridge is up, it's past 8am, AND you've been quiet for 10+ minutes. That's a narrow window if you're a heavy user.\n\nSo: heartbeat is the primary trigger, startup is the safety net for \"bridge was down during the quiet window\" or \"user never went idle.\" Both are guarded by the same `spawnedToday` flag + audit file check, so they can't double-fire.\n\nWorth keeping both.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> ok. 1 more thing, we installed the cron updated for missed cron jobs to finish in a later time when realized the miss, is it something how the sleep works as well?",
    "\n\nYes, same concept — the startup sleep trigger already does this. If the bridge was down at 8am and you start it at 2pm, `shouldRunOnStartup()` sees \"it's past 8am, no audit today\" and fires the sleep catch-up.\n\nSo sleep already has intelligent catch-up built in, just through a different mechanism than `checkMissedCrons()`:\n\n| System | Catch-up mechanism |\n|--------|-------------------|\n| Host crontab tasks | `checkMissedCrons()` — reads crontab, compares `cron_runs.json` timestamps |\n| Sleep maintenance | `shouldRunOnStartup()` — checks hour ≥ 8 + no audit file today |\n| Internal cron (one-offs) | `checkCron()` — fires any entry where `fireAt` is past and `fired=false` |\n\nAll three run on startup. Same pattern, different implementations because they track state differently (cron_runs.json vs audit files vs cron.json).\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> does it the same code, or 2 implementation for the same problem",
    "\n\nTwo implementations for the same problem. Sleep has its own catch-up in `SleepTrigger.shouldRunOnStartup()` (checks audit files), while host crontab has `checkMissedCrons()` (checks `cron_runs.json`).\n\nWe could unify them by putting sleep on the host crontab too — `0 8 * * * agentbridge-sleep # agentbridge-managed` — and letting `checkMissedCrons()` handle the catch-up. Then remove the startup trigger entirely.\n\nBut sleep has the extra \"10 min idle\" requirement that host crontab can't enforce. If cron fires sleep at 8am while you're actively chatting, it'd run maintenance mid-conversation.\n\nSo the two implementations exist because sleep has constraints (idle check, once-per-day audit) that generic cron catch-up doesn't handle. Not ideal, but justified. Merging them would mean adding sleep-specific logic into the generic cron checker, which defeats the purpose.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> I see, is there anything we can refactor here?",
    "\n[Tool uses: thinking]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "There's the real refactor — two separate `SleepTrigger` instances. The `spawnedToday` flag in main.ts's instance doesn't protect against the heartbeat's instance in memory-manager, and vice versa. They can't see each other's state.\n\nThe fix: create one `SleepTrigger` and share it.\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "Now I'll refactor: pass the `SleepTrigger` into `MemoryManager` so both startup and heartbeat share one instance.\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "\n[Tool uses: fs_write]",
    "\n[Tool uses: fs_write]",
    "\n[Tool uses: fs_write]",
    "Now update main.ts to share the instance:\n[Tool uses: fs_write]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "Done. The refactor:\n\n- One `SleepTrigger` instance created in `main.ts`, passed into `memory.startHeartbeat(sleepTrigger)`\n- Both startup and heartbeat cron share the same `spawnedToday` flag\n- If startup fires sleep → heartbeat sees `spawnedToday=true` → skips\n- If startup skips (before 8am) → heartbeat can still fire later → sets the flag → no duplicates\n\nPreviously the two instances couldn't see each other's state, so the flag was useless across the two paths.\n[Tool uses: none]",
