    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "Right — this was my manual test run at 12:21 today. It covers the period since the last sleep (Mar 15 19:34) through to now, which includes the late-night session where we built Brownie, fixed bugs, etc. But it says \"no new messages in the transcript window\" and skipped the daily summary because `daily_20260315.md` already existed.\n\nSo the actual productive audit for Mar 15 is the 19:34 one. Today's 12:21 run was just my test — it found nothing to do because the daily was already written.\n\nWant me to remove it since it's just a test artifact? The real Mar 15 audit (19:34) already captured everything meaningful.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> so mar16 would be created tomorrow normally, or it creates as mar17 tmr?",
    "\n\nThe audit filename uses the timestamp of when it runs, not the day it covers. So:\n\n- Tomorrow morning (Mar 17, ≥8am), sleep triggers → writes `sleep_20260317_*.md`\n- That audit covers Mar 16's activity (everything since the last sleep)\n\nToday's `sleep_20260316_122126.md` already exists, so the `hasSleepAuditToday()` check will prevent another run today. Tomorrow it'll see no `20260317` file and fire normally.\n\nSo yes — tomorrow's audit will be named `sleep_20260317`, covering Mar 16. The naming reflects \"when it ran\" not \"what day it covers.\" A bit confusing but consistent.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> ok, so it means our sleeping was not just a test run but should have had covered the late night chats",
    "\n\nYou're right. The 12:21 run was the real Mar 16 sleep — it should have covered our entire late-night session (Brownie, bug fixes, todo, cron, all of it). But it said \"no new messages in the transcript window\" and skipped the daily summary.\n\nThat means either:\n1. The transcript files don't have last night's messages\n2. The sleep agent looked at the wrong time window\n3. The daily summary `daily_20260315.md` was already written by the 19:34 run, and the sleep agent treated that as \"nothing new to summarize\"\n\nThe 19:34 run happened BEFORE our big session. So all the work from ~20:00 to ~01:30 was never summarized. The 12:21 run should have caught it but didn't because it saw the daily file already existed and skipped.\n\nThat's a gap in the sleep logic — it assumes one daily summary covers the whole day, but if sleep runs early (19:34) and you keep working until 1:30am, the second run skips because the daily file exists. The late-night work falls through the cracks.\n\nWant me to dig into how the daily summary check works and fix this? The simplest fix would be: if there are new messages since the last audit timestamp, write an addendum even if the daily file exists.\n[Tool uses: none]",
