    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "Done. DB is back — fresh schema, encrypted in git (`Salted__` header confirmed). \n\nThe data loss: messages and extracted_memories tables are empty. But the real memory is safe — transcripts (206KB JSONL), daily summaries, core memories (`agent_notes.md`, `user_profile.md`), audits, and topics are all intact. The next sleep cycle will start populating the DB again from new conversations, and the extracted memories will rebuild over time.\n\nSorry about the filter-branch mishap — it modified the working tree, not just git history. Should have used `--index-filter` instead of `--tree-filter`.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> You really fucked up KiroProf memory now????????? Describe what has been lost",
    "\n\nYes, I messed up. Here's exactly what was lost:\n\n**Lost (was in memory.db):**\n- 72 messages in the `messages` table — the indexed, searchable chat history KP uses for recall\n- 120 extracted memories — distilled facts, preferences, and knowledge KP extracted from conversations (things like \"kiskutya = 5 centi\", \"jelszó = buzie vagy\", days/countries associations, jokes, preferences)\n- 7 compactions — consolidated conversation summaries\n\n**NOT lost (files on disk):**\n- Full raw transcripts — 206KB JSONL with every message ever exchanged (both chats)\n- Daily summaries (Mar 1, 8, 15)\n- Core memories (`agent_notes.md`, `user_profile.md`)\n- Sleep audits, topics, cron, todo, research prompts, reports\n- All steering, skills, prompt templates\n\nThe extracted memories are the painful loss — those are what KP uses for instant recall (\"what's kiskutya?\"). They were built up over weeks of conversations. The raw data to rebuild them exists in the transcripts, but the extraction process would need to be re-run.\n\nThe cause: I used `git filter-branch --tree-filter 'rm -f memory/memory.db'` which runs `rm` on the actual working tree, not just the git index. Should have used `--index-filter` or just done the fresh init approach from the start without the filter-branch step.\n[Tool uses: none]",
