    "Saved at `/tmp/agentbridge-gc-test/gc-diff-report.txt`. The pre/post message lists are also there:\n- `/tmp/agentbridge-gc-test/pre_messages.txt` — all 626 messages before GC\n- `/tmp/agentbridge-gc-test/post_messages.txt` — 614 messages after immediate deletes\n- `/tmp/agentbridge-gc-test/memory/garbage.json` — 104 marked for deletion after 7 days\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> I don't now how you did the test, but I wanna run just 1 command, the sleep:garbage-collection and see the difference after; as i follwed you you did several steps -> did you exactly emulate how it is coded? then it is ok",
    "\n[Tool uses: thinking]",
    "To be straight with you — the GC isn't coded as a script. It's instructions in the sleeping prompt that Dreamy (an AI agent) follows using judgment. There's no `gc()` function in TypeScript.\n\nWhat I did was manually emulate the steps from §3 of the sleeping prompt:\n1. Found dupes with SQL → deleted them\n2. Found wrong-chat with SQL → deleted them\n3. Read through all short messages, used my judgment to classify noise vs keep → wrote garbage.json\n4. Found repeated probes with SQL → added to garbage.json\n\nThis is exactly what Dreamy would do — scan with sqlite3, apply judgment, write garbage.json. The difference is Dreamy does it autonomously during sleep.\n\nTo run it as a single command, you'd do:\n```bash\nbash scripts/test-sleep-gc.sh                    # copy DB\nAGENTBRIDGE_MEMORY_DIR=/tmp/agentbridge-gc-test/memory agentbridge-sleep\nbash scripts/test-sleep-gc.sh --diff             # see results\n```\n\nBut `agentbridge-sleep` spawns a kiro-cli session, which I can't do from inside kiro-cli. That's why I emulated it manually.\n\nWant me to make the test script wrap all 3 steps into one command (it would still need you to run it from a terminal)?\n[Tool uses: none]",
