    "Done (`e7d819f`). Here's what changed:\n\n**`/status`** now shows:\n```\nKiro Professor v0.1.0\n🤖 Model: claude-opus-4.6\n📊 Context window: 42%\n⏱️ Uptime: 2h 15m\n🔌 Transport: TMUX — ✅ Connected\n💓 Heartbeat: running (5min)\n📋 Tasks: sleep-trigger\n😴 Last sleep: sleep_20260316_083012.md\n```\n\nModel is queried via `kiro-cli settings list --format json` → `chat.defaultModel` (falls back to `KIRO_MODEL` env var, then \"unknown\").\n\n**`/cron`** now shows:\n```\n⏰ 16 Mar 2026, 23:20:00\n\n0 8 * * * ~/.agentbridge/daily-backup.sh >> ...\n```\n\nJust current time (Budapest TZ) + `crontab -l` output. No memory dependency.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> why the \" chat.defaultModel\" there is no chat.currentModel?",
    "\n\nBased on what `kiro-cli settings list --format json` returned, there's only these keys:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"chat.defaultModel\": \"claude-opus-4.6\",\n  \"chat.enableKnowledge\": true,\n  \"chat.enableThinking\": true,\n  \"chat.enableContextUsageIndicator\": true\n}\n```\n\nNo `chat.currentModel` — kiro-cli only exposes `chat.defaultModel`. That's the model it uses unless overridden with `--model` at launch. So `defaultModel` *is* the current model in practice, unless `KIRO_MODEL` env var overrides it (which the code checks first).\n\nWant me to check if there's a separate kiro-cli command that might show the active model, like `kiro-cli chat` subcommands?\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> chekc ath is going on I get these \"⏳ Previous request still in progress...\"",
