    "The `busyChats` guard fires before messages reach the transport. It's likely the `/status` command is slow now — the `kiro-cli settings list --format json` call takes up to 3 seconds, and during that time the chat is marked busy (or it was already busy from a prior request that didn't clear).\n\nLet me check — the `/status` handler runs *before* the `busyChats` check, right?\n[Tool uses: grep]",
    "`/status` is at line 522, `busyChats` check is at line 895 — so `/status` runs well before the busy guard. The \"still in progress\" message means a *different* message you sent hit the busy guard because a previous transport request hadn't finished yet.\n\nThis isn't related to the `/status` or `/cron` changes. It's the normal flow — you sent a message while KP was still processing a prior one. Did you send something to the transport (not a slash command) right before or after `/status`? Or was KP still processing the research task from Brownie?\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> Not releated: it is not deployed yet, it is something else. Also Brownie was never reported back the research task",
    "\n\nTwo separate issues then:\n\n**1. \"Previous request still in progress\"** — something has `busyChats` stuck. The running instance doesn't have the new code yet (not deployed), so this is the old code. A transport request probably never completed — could be kiro-cli hanging or a response that was never detected as finished. Sending `/stop` or `/cancel` should clear it (those call `busyChats.delete(sessionKey)`).\n\n**2. Brownie research task never reported back** — the task `3bdfbe` was spawned earlier. Let me check if there's a way to see its status:\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "Brownie's task died immediately. The ACP subprocess dumped the entire `browsing_prompt.md` steering file as raw text into stdout, and kiro-cli's JSON-RPC parser rejected every line as `Parse error` — it expected JSON-RPC messages but got markdown.\n\nThe root cause: `agentbridge-browse.ts` writes the prompt to stdin, but kiro-cli ACP expects a proper JSON-RPC `sendMessage` request, not raw text. The prompt was sent as plain text instead of being wrapped in a JSON-RPC envelope.\n\nThis is a separate bug in `agentbridge-browse.ts` — the stdin write needs to be a proper ACP `sendMessage` JSON-RPC call. Want me to fix that next, or focus on deploying the `/status` + `/cron` changes first?\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> no fix that it is more important, i will deploy both after",
    "\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "\n[Tool uses: thinking]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "\n[Tool uses: thinking]",
    "The log shows every line of `browsing_prompt.md` hitting kiro-cli as raw text — the ACP handshake never completed. The issue is a race: `main()` is sync, the async IIFE is fire-and-forget, and the process can exit before the handshake finishes. When the parent dies, stdin closes and kiro-cli gets garbage.\n\nFix: make `main()` async, await the handshake through sending the prompt, then exit cleanly.\n[Tool uses: fs_write]",
    "Now fix the entry point call since main is now async:\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "That's fine — calling an async function without await is valid here since it's the entry point. Node will keep the event loop alive until the promise resolves.\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "Fixed (`6658e93`). The bug: `main()` was sync with a fire-and-forget async IIFE doing the ACP handshake. The process could exit before `initialize` → `session/new` → `session/prompt` completed, so kiro-cli never got proper JSON-RPC messages — it got nothing, or the raw prompt leaked through somehow.\n\nNow `main()` is async — it awaits the full handshake (initialize, session/new, sends session/prompt), then closes the readline, unrefs the child, and exits. The child continues processing the prompt detached. Deploy both this and the `/status`+`/cron` changes together.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> so thats why both ag. is dead now?",
    "\n\nNo, the browse bug wouldn't kill the main bridge. `agentbridge-browse` runs as a separate detached process — it spawns, does its thing (or fails), and exits. The main bridge is unaffected.\n\nThe \"Previous request still in progress\" you saw earlier means the main bridge's `busyChats` is stuck — a transport request never completed. That's a separate issue. Could be kiro-cli hanging in the tmux session, or a response that was never detected as finished.\n\nBoth bridges (Telegram + Discord) being dead sounds like the main process crashed or was killed. Let me check:\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "No bridge process running — it's dead. There's a stuck `agentbridge-browse` from 23:10 (the old code, still hanging on the handshake). \n\nThe bridge itself isn't running. You'll need to restart it. The stuck browse process should be killed too:\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "The bridge crash is likely unrelated to the browse bug. Without a log file it's hard to tell what killed it — could have been a restart you did, or an unhandled exception. Deploy and restart when ready:\n\n```bash\n./scripts/deploy.sh\n~/.agentbridge/agentbridge.sh --all\n```\n[Tool uses: none]",
