    "Now let me check the Telegram message size limit and the response formatter:\n[Tool uses: grep]",
    "Now I have the full picture. Here's what's happening and what needs fixing:\n\n1. `readLogTail()` only reads last 500 chars — that's fine for the reminder\n2. But the browse result gets injected as a synthetic Telegram message (`[Scheduled reminder] ...`) which goes through the full transport pipeline — kiro-cli processes it\n3. The real crash was KP running `agentbridge-browse --task \"$(cat huge-file)\"` — the shell expansion put the entire research prompt as a CLI argument\n\nLet me make this robust:\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "The `readLogTail` reads raw ACP JSON-RPC output — not a clean summary. Let me also check what the log actually contains for a completed task:\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "\n[Tool uses: thinking]",
    "Three problems to fix:\n\n1. **No task size limit** — KP ran `--task \"$(cat huge-file)\"` which blew up\n2. **Log tail is raw JSON-RPC** — `readLogTail` returns garbage, not the agent's actual response\n3. **No cap on result message** — could inject huge text into the bridge\n[Tool uses: fs_write]",
    "Now fix the log reader to extract actual agent text and cap it:\n[Tool uses: fs_write]",
    "Now cap the reminder message itself as defense in depth:\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "The task description in the message could also be huge. Let me cap it:\n[Tool uses: fs_write]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "Done (`c78dcc6`). Three layers of defense:\n\n| Layer | What | Limit |\n|-------|------|-------|\n| `agentbridge-browse` | `--task` argument | 2000 chars (truncated with …) |\n| `readLogTail` | Extracts actual agent response text from ACP JSON-RPC `agent_message_chunk` notifications instead of raw JSON tail | 2000 chars |\n| `checkBrowseTasks` | Task label in reminder messages | 200 chars |\n\nThe log reader now actually parses the ACP output and concatenates the agent's text chunks — so you'll get a readable summary instead of `{\"jsonrpc\":\"2.0\",\"error\":...}` garbage. Deploy when ready.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> you mentioned something bigger refactor, let's discuss",
    "\n\nYeah — right now when a browse task finishes, the result gets injected as a **synthetic user message**:\n\n```\n[Scheduled reminder] 🌐 Browser task completed: check X notifications\n\n<agent's response text>\n```\n\nThis goes through `telegramPoller.injectUpdate()` → the normal message handler → kiro-cli processes it as if YOU sent it. So KP receives the browse result as a \"user message\" and then responds to it, which means:\n\n1. KP wastes a turn interpreting/summarizing something that's already a summary\n2. It eats context window\n3. If the result is large, KP might truncate or misinterpret it\n4. The user sees KP's *response to the result*, not the result itself\n\nWhat it should do instead: **send the browse result directly to the user as a Telegram message**, bypassing the transport entirely. The bridge already has `telegramApi.sendMessage()` — the cron checker just needs access to it.\n\nThe refactor would be:\n- Give `checkBrowseTasks()` a callback like `sendDirectMessage(chatId, text)` instead of writing to `pending_reminders.json`\n- The main loop wires it: `checkBrowseTasks((chatId, msg) => telegramApi.sendMessage(chatId, msg))`\n- Browse results go straight to the user, no kiro-cli round-trip\n\nIt's not huge — maybe 30 lines changed across 2 files. But it changes the cron checker's interface from file-based (pending_reminders.json) to callback-based. The reminder system for cron tasks might still want the file-based approach (since those ARE meant to be processed by KP). So it might make sense to split: cron reminders stay as synthetic messages, browse results get direct delivery.\n\nWant me to do it now, or save it for later?\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> /agent swap kiro_planner",
    "> create a plan how we will do it. Message directly to the user on TG or Discord and first few lines to the agent (or it can send a summary?). Also can it be writing a file to reports directly?",
    "\n\nLet me understand the current flow and what we're working with:\n[Tool uses: grep]",
    "\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "\n[Tool uses: grep]",
    "\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "Now let me check if the browsing_prompt.md already tells the agent to write to a file:\n[Tool uses: grep]",
    "\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "Now let me check how the research task was structured — the task said \"write the report to ~/reports/...\":\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "\n\nCan't access those dirs from here. But I have enough context. Let me lay out the questions:\n\n**Understanding**: Browse tasks should (1) write full results to disk as a report file, (2) send the result directly to the user on TG/Discord (not through kiro-cli), and (3) optionally notify the agent with a short summary so it knows what happened.\n\n[1]: Where should reports be saved?\n- a. `~/reports/browse_{taskId}_{date}.md` (dedicated reports dir)\n- b. `~/.agentbridge/memory/reports/` (inside agentbridge data)\n- c. Other path?\n\n[2]: What should the agent (KP) get?\n- a. First 3-5 lines of the result as a synthetic message (so it has context if user asks follow-up)\n- b. Just a one-liner like \"Browse task completed, report saved to ~/reports/X.md\" (agent can read the file if needed)\n- c. Nothing — agent doesn't need to know\n\n[3]: Should the browsing_prompt.md be updated to tell the agent to write its own report file (the agent has `write` tool access), or should the bridge extract the agent's response from the log and write the file itself?\n- a. Agent writes the report (more flexible — it can structure it however makes sense)\n- b. Bridge writes the report from extracted log text (guaranteed — works even if agent forgets)\n- c. Both — agent writes detailed report, bridge saves raw log as backup\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> 1. Workflow if the task is just a check a page for browsing agent, it can send it back to KP as is today. KP should specify to the browsing agent, where the result needed. If it is a longer text or research, it should be in: ~/.agentbridge/subagents/browse_{taskId}_{date}.md -> report to KP: complete -> KP pick the file, creates a summary sned to the User and moves (not cp) the file to the appropriate dir. If it is a report to the reports.  Ask the other question if any",
    "\n\nGot it. So the flow is:\n\n1. **Short tasks** (check a page, quick lookup) → Brownie sends result back as-is → KP gets it as today → KP forwards to user\n2. **Long tasks** (research, reports) → Brownie writes to `~/.agentbridge/subagents/browse_{taskId}_{date}.md` → KP gets notified \"complete\" → KP reads the file, summarizes, sends summary to user, then `mv` the file to the right place (e.g. `~/reports/`)\n\nThis means the routing decision (short vs long) is made by KP when it invokes `agentbridge-browse`, not by the bridge. The bridge infrastructure just needs to:\n- Ensure `~/.agentbridge/subagents/` exists\n- Deliver the result/notification to KP reliably\n- Not crash on large payloads\n\n[1]: How does KP tell Brownie \"write to file\" vs \"return inline\"? \n- a. KP includes it in the `--task` text itself (e.g. \"...write the report to ~/.agentbridge/subagents/browse_abc123_20260316.md\")\n- b. New `--output-file` flag on `agentbridge-browse` that gets injected into the prompt template\n- c. The browsing_prompt.md template always tells the agent to write long results to `~/.agentbridge/subagents/` and return a short summary inline — agent decides based on length\n\nI'm leaning toward (c) — bake it into the template so Brownie always does the right thing without KP having to micromanage. But KP could still override via the task text. What do you think?\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> 1 c. is ok, but let's also create a defult fallback: write the file to the subagents - how shoudl we do it?",
    "\n\nSo the defense-in-depth fallback: even if Brownie forgets to write the file, the bridge extracts the agent's response from the ACP log and writes it to `~/.agentbridge/subagents/` anyway.\n\nWe already have `readLogTail()` that extracts `agent_message_chunk` text from the log. The fallback would be:\n\n**In `checkBrowseTasks()`** when a browse process finishes:\n1. Check if a file matching `browse_{taskId}_*.md` exists in `~/.agentbridge/subagents/`\n2. If yes → agent wrote it, use that path in the notification\n3. If no → extract full agent text from ACP log → write it to `~/.agentbridge/subagents/browse_{taskId}_{date}.md`\n4. Either way, notify KP: \"Browse task complete. Report: ~/.agentbridge/subagents/browse_{taskId}_{date}.md\"\n\nFor short results (under some threshold, say 500 chars), skip the file and just inline the text in the notification — so quick checks still work as today.\n\n[1]: What's the threshold for \"short enough to inline\"?\n- a. 500 chars (roughly a paragraph)\n- b. 1000 chars\n- c. Always write the file, always notify with path (simplest, most consistent)\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> Lets go with 1c. less pain point",
    "\n\nClear. Always write the file, always notify with path. Here's the plan:\n\n---\n\n**Implementation Plan — Browse Task Result Delivery**\n\n**Problem Statement:**\nBrowse task results are currently injected as synthetic user messages with raw ACP JSON tail, causing KP to waste turns interpreting garbage. Large results can crash the bridge. No persistent report files are saved.\n\n**Requirements:**\n- Brownie always writes long results to `~/.agentbridge/subagents/browse_{taskId}_{date}.md` (instructed via template)\n- Bridge fallback: if Brownie didn't write the file, bridge extracts agent text from ACP log and writes it\n- KP gets notified: \"Browse task complete. Report: {path}\" — KP reads, summarizes, sends to user, moves file\n- Always write file + notify with path (no inline threshold)\n\n**Task Breakdown:**\n\n**Task 1: Update `browsing_prompt.md` template**\n\nObjective: Tell Brownie to always write results to `~/.agentbridge/subagents/browse_{taskId}_{date}.md` and output a one-liner confirmation.\n\nImplementation:\n- Add `${TASK_ID}` and `${DATE}` variables to the template\n- Update Output Format section: \"Write your full findings to `~/.agentbridge/subagents/browse_${TASK_ID}_${DATE}.md`. Then output a single line: `REPORT_SAVED: ~/.agentbridge/subagents/browse_${TASK_ID}_${DATE}.md`\"\n- Update `loadBrowsePrompt()` in `agentbridge-browse.ts` to substitute `TASK_ID` and `DATE` variables\n- Ensure `~/.agentbridge/subagents/` is created (mkdirSync in browse spawn)\n\nTest: existing `loadBrowsePrompt` test covers variable substitution — verify new vars are replaced.\n\nDemo: `agentbridge-browse --dry-run` shows the updated prompt with file path instructions.\n\n**Task 2: Bridge fallback — write file if agent didn't**\n\nObjective: In `checkBrowseTasks()`, always ensure a report file exists in `subagents/`.\n\nImplementation:\n- After process finishes, check if `browse_{taskId}_*.md` exists in `~/.agentbridge/subagents/`\n- If not: extract full agent text from ACP log (reuse existing `readLogTail` logic but uncapped), write to `~/.agentbridge/subagents/browse_{taskId}_{date}.md`\n- Extract a helper: `extractAgentText(logFile): string` — full text, no truncation (for file write). `readLogTail` calls this with truncation (for inline use if ever needed).\n\nTest: unit test — given a mock ACP log file, `extractAgentText` returns concatenated agent chunks.\n\nDemo: Even if Brownie crashes mid-task, a report file with partial results exists in subagents/.\n\n**Task 3: Change notification from inline result to file path**\n\nObjective: Replace the current `appendReminder` message with a path-based notification.\n\nImplementation:\n- Change completed message to: `🌐 Browse task complete. Report: {filePath}`\n- Change timeout message to: `🌐 Browse task timed out ({seconds}s). Partial report: {filePath}`\n- The reminder still goes through `pending_reminders.json` → synthetic message → KP processes it\n- KP sees \"Report: /path/to/file\" → reads it → summarizes → sends to user → moves file\n\nTest: existing `browse-checker.test.ts` — update expected message format.\n\nDemo: KP receives a clean one-liner with file path instead of raw ACP JSON.\n\n**Task 4: Deploy `browsing_prompt.md`**\n\nObjective: Ensure `deploy.sh` copies the updated template.\n\nImplementation:\n- Verify `deploy.sh` already copies `browsing_prompt.md` to `~/.agentbridge/`\n- If not, add it\n\nTest: manual — `deploy.sh` and verify file exists.\n\nDemo: Deployed Brownie uses the new template with file-write instructions.\n\n---\n\nDoes this plan look good, or would you like me to adjust anything?\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> ok and once the report arrives, what KP does with it it is a softskill specified in the reseacrh skill, right?",
    "\n\nRight — what KP does with the report (read it, summarize, send to user, move to `~/reports/`) is a soft skill defined in the steering/skill files. The bridge just delivers the notification with the file path. KP's behavior is guided by its persona and skills, not hardcoded in the bridge.\n\nSo we don't need to touch any skill files as part of this plan — that's KP's domain. The bridge work is just Tasks 1-4: make sure the file exists and KP gets told where it is.\n\nWant me to proceed with implementation?\n[Tool uses: none]",
