    "\n[Tool uses: thinking]",
    "Here's what I found:\n\n**No official Microsoft MCP server for PowerPoint.** MS has MCP servers for Dynamics 365, Power Platform, and Graph API (mail/calendar/files), but not for PPTX creation.\n\nThe community options, ranked for your setup (WSL + mcporter + kiro):\n\n---\n\n**Option A: `pptx-generator-mcp`** (Node.js) — [github](https://github.com/dmytro-ustynov/pptx-generator-mcp)\n- LLM writes markdown → MCP server converts to .pptx\n- 3 tools: `generate_presentation`, `get_template`, `get_config`\n- No Python, no python-pptx. Pure Node.js (uses `pptxgenjs` under the hood)\n- Supports code blocks, tables, bold, bullets, custom branding\n- Limitation: markdown-driven only, no fine-grained slide manipulation\n\n**Option B: `office-powerpoint-mcp-server`** by GongRzhe (Python) — [github](https://github.com/GongRzhe/Office-PowerPoint-MCP-Server)\n- 32 tools across 11 modules (create, add_slide, add_text, add_image, add_chart, apply_theme, etc.)\n- Uses python-pptx under the hood — BUT the key difference from your earlier pain: the LLM never writes python-pptx code. It calls structured tools like `add_slide(layout=\"title_and_content\")`. The abstraction layer is what makes it work.\n- 584 stars, most mature option\n- Requires Python + `pip install office-powerpoint-mcp-server`\n\n**Option C: `pptx-xlsx-mcp`** by jenstangen1 (Python/COM)\n- ❌ Requires Windows + running PowerPoint via COM automation. Won't work in WSL.\n\n---\n\nMy recommendation: **start with Option A** (Node.js markdown approach). It fits your stack (no Python dep), and for most presentation needs, markdown → pptx is enough. If you hit limits (need precise positioning, charts, images), upgrade to Option B.\n\nSetup would be:\n```bash\n# Install\ncd ~/workspace && git clone https://github.com/dmytro-ustynov/pptx-generator-mcp.git\ncd pptx-generator-mcp && npm install && npm install -g .\n\n# Register in mcporter\nmcporter config add pptx-generator --command \"pptx-generator-mcp\"\n\n# Test\nmcporter call pptx-generator.get_template\n```\n\nThen add a steering file for kiro telling it how to use the MCP tools for presentation requests.\n\nMelyik irány tetszik?\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> are these A and B all work locally? Due to confidentiality reasons we cannot push data online",
    "\n\nYes, both are fully local:\n\n**Option A (`pptx-generator-mcp`)** — 100% local. It's a stdio MCP server — mcporter spawns it as a child process, communicates via stdin/stdout. The Node.js `pptxgenjs` library generates the .pptx file on disk. No network calls whatsoever.\n\n**Option B (`office-powerpoint-mcp-server`)** — 100% local. Same stdio pattern. Python + python-pptx generates files locally. No API calls, no cloud.\n\nBoth run as local processes on your machine, no data leaves your system. The MCP protocol itself is just JSON-RPC over stdio (or localhost HTTP) — there's no remote server involved.\n\nThe only MCP servers that phone home are the ones explicitly using cloud APIs (like the MS Graph ones for Office 365, or MagicSlides which calls their API). These two don't.\n[Tool uses: none]",
