    "> let's review the lcm enhancments planning. compare to the lossless-claw project, is there anything we should be adding?",
    "\n[Tool uses: thinking]",
    "\n[Tool uses: fs_read,fs_read]",
    "Now let me look at the key LCM modules we haven't covered:\n[Tool uses: code,code,code,code,code,code]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "\n[Tool uses: thinking]",
    "Here's the gap analysis — LCM features not in our current plan:\n\n### Already covered (✓)\n- Source linking → Stage 1\n- Expand tool → Stage 1 (agentbridge-expand)\n- Bootstrap reconciliation → Stage 3 (detect-only)\n- Large message overflow → Stage 5\n\n### Missing — worth adding\n\n**1. FTS5 fallback (LIKE search)** — LCM has `full-text-fallback.ts` that degrades gracefully to `LIKE %term%` when FTS5 isn't available. Agentbridge hard-crashes if FTS5 is missing. Low effort, high resilience. Could slot into Stage 1.\n\n**2. Hierarchical compaction** — this is LCM's core: leaf summaries → condensed summaries → multi-level tree, with token budgets, fresh tail protection, and incremental passes. Agentbridge memory grows unbounded — the `compactions` table exists but the engine doesn't. This is the biggest gap but also the biggest effort (LCM's `compaction.ts` is 800+ lines, `summarize.ts` is 640+ lines, `engine.ts` is 2100+ lines).\n\n**3. Expansion policy/routing** — LCM doesn't just expand blindly. `expansion-policy.ts` detects broad time ranges (\"last quarter\"), multi-hop queries, estimates token cost, and routes to `answer_directly` / `expand_shallow` / `delegate_traversal`. Our Stage 1 expand is a flat read — no intelligence.\n\n**4. Expansion safety rails** — LCM has two layers:\n- `expansion-auth.ts` — grant-based auth with TTL, token caps, conversation scope\n- `lcm-expansion-recursion-guard.ts` — depth cap (1 level), idempotent reentry detection, telemetry\n\nWithout these, if kiro calls agentbridge-expand in a loop, there's no brake.\n\n**5. Heartbeat pruning** — LCM has `pruneHeartbeatOk` config that retroactively deletes HEARTBEAT_OK turn cycles from storage. Agentbridge stores every heartbeat — that's noise polluting search results and wasting space.\n\n**6. Metrics collection** — `collectMetrics()` in integrity.ts gathers runtime stats. Would feed nicely into the web dashboard.\n\n**7. Session patterns** — LCM has `ignoreSessionPatterns` (never store) and `statelessSessionPatterns` (read-only). Agentbridge stores everything from every session.\n\n### My recommendation for plan updates\n\n| Priority | Feature | Effort | Where to add |\n|----------|---------|--------|-------------|\n| High | FTS5 fallback | Small | Stage 1 (new Task 6) |\n| High | Expansion recursion guard | Small | Stage 1 (alongside expand tool) |\n| High | Heartbeat pruning | Small | Stage 2 (alongside sleep work) |\n| Medium | Expansion policy/routing | Medium | New Stage 3.5 |\n| Medium | Metrics for dashboard | Medium | New Stage 4.5 |\n| Low | Session patterns | Small | Stage 3 |\n| Future | Hierarchical compaction | Large | New Stage 6 — this is a project in itself |\n\nThe compaction engine is the elephant in the room. It's what makes LCM's memory actually scale. Without it, agentbridge memory degrades as conversations grow. But it's easily 2-3 weeks of work to port properly.\n\nWant me to update `docs/TODO/lcm-enhancements.md` with these additions?\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> let's discuss 1by 1:  1. FTS5 fallback, study our project (memory.asbuilt) we have the same solution",
    "\n[Tool uses: grep]",
    "\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "You're right — agentbridge already has this covered, and arguably better than LCM.\n\nAgentbridge's `RecallFallbackPipeline` is a 5-stage cascade:\n1. Primary FTS5\n2. Context-augmented FTS5 (keywords from working memory)\n3. Relaxed FTS5 (OR mode, drop short tokens)\n4. Substring LIKE search (catches compound words FTS5 misses — e.g. Hungarian agglutination)\n5. Vector search (if enabled)\n\nLCM's `full-text-fallback.ts` is simpler — just a LIKE `%term%` fallback when FTS5 isn't available at all (runtime probe).\n\nThe only thing LCM has that agentbridge doesn't is the **FTS5 availability probe** (`features.ts` — `probeFts5()`). But agentbridge uses `better-sqlite3` which always ships with FTS5 enabled, unlike Node's built-in `node:sqlite` which LCM uses and which may not have it.\n\n**Verdict**: Drop this from the plan. Agentbridge already exceeds LCM here. No action needed.\n\nNext one?\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> What I wanna plan: are we currently searching the daily/weekly/Q .md files?",
