    "\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "This is very revealing. Let me check how the original language search works:\n[Tool uses: grep]",
    "Now I have the full picture. Here's my revised analysis:\n\nYou already have a surprisingly rich extraction system:\n\n- `content_original` — stores the original language (Hungarian) text\n- `content_en` — English translation for FTS5 search\n- `preserve_original` flag + `preserved_keyword` — for explicit keyword preservation\n- Two separate FTS5 indexes: `extracted_memories_fts` (English) and `extracted_memories_original_fts` (original language)\n- `source_timestamp` — already links back to a time range\n\nSo the question about Stage 1 becomes: **what does `source_message_ids` add that `source_timestamp` doesn't already give you?**\n\nWith `source_timestamp`, kiro can already do:\n- \"This fact was extracted from messages around timestamp X\"\n- Query `messages` table with `WHERE timestamp BETWEEN (source_timestamp - 60000) AND (source_timestamp + 60000)` to find the surrounding conversation\n\nWhat `source_message_ids` would add:\n- Exact message IDs instead of a fuzzy time window\n- Multiple source messages (a fact derived from a conversation spanning several messages)\n\nBut here's the thing — the `agentbridge-expand` CLI would essentially just be doing that timestamp-range query anyway. You could build expand as a thin wrapper around the existing `source_timestamp` without any schema changes:\n\n```\nagentbridge-expand --timestamp 1710892800000 --window 300\n→ SELECT * FROM messages WHERE timestamp BETWEEN ? AND ? ORDER BY timestamp\n```\n\nNo migration, no pipeline changes, no sleep prompt changes. Just one new CLI file + steering.\n\n**My revised verdict:** Skip the `source_message_ids` column entirely. Build `agentbridge-expand` using `source_timestamp` + a time window. That's 1 task instead of 5, and it covers 95% of the use case. If the timestamp-based approach proves too fuzzy in practice, you can add explicit IDs later.\n\nWant to go that route, or do you see a case where timestamp-based lookup wouldn't be enough?\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> So we already have a timestamp (I beleive date is enough?) field in the dataabse right?",
    "\n\nYes — `source_timestamp` is a Unix millisecond timestamp on every `extracted_memories` row. It points to when the original message was recorded.\n\nBut \"date is enough\" depends on volume. If you have 200 messages on a given day, a date-level lookup returns all 200. The millisecond timestamp narrows it to the exact conversation window (±5min would typically give you 3-10 messages of context).\n\nSo the timestamp is actually better than just a date — it's already precise enough to find the surrounding conversation without needing explicit message IDs. The data is already there, nothing to add.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> comeon we are humnas, don't need a fucking ms. keep minutes only. Hm?",
    "\n\nFair point. The timestamp is already stored in ms but for the expand lookup, rounding to the minute and grabbing a ±5min window around it gives you the full conversation context. Nobody needs millisecond precision to find \"what were we talking about when I said that.\"\n\nSo `agentbridge-expand` would just be: take the `source_timestamp` from the extracted memory, query messages ±5min around it, return them. One file, no schema changes. Want me to build it or are we still in planning mode?\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> have a timestep for minute precision not 5m",
    "\n\nRight — ±1min window around the `source_timestamp`. Tight enough to get the immediate context, not so wide that it pulls in unrelated stuff. Want me to build it?\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> wait... I am not talking about the window yet, just how we store the memories in each record.. minute precisity - or is there a benefit for sec precisity?",
    "\n\nAh, you're asking about the `source_timestamp` storage precision itself.\n\nIt's already stored as Unix ms (e.g. `1710892845123`). Changing it to minute precision (truncating seconds) would lose the ability to distinguish messages sent in the same minute. That matters because:\n\n- In a fast back-and-forth, you might have 5-10 messages within one minute\n- The `messages` table stores timestamps in ms too — matching on exact timestamp lets you pinpoint the exact source message, not just \"somewhere in this minute\"\n\nSecond precision is the sweet spot — ms is overkill but costs nothing (it's already there), minute loses ordering within a conversation burst. I'd leave it as-is. No benefit to changing the storage format.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> ok, because I am thinking about a new feture of FORGET ;)",
    "\n\nInteresting — so you want to be able to say \"forget what I said at 10:35\" and have it wipe the messages + any extracted memories linked to that time window?\n\nWith second-precision `source_timestamp`, you could do:\n1. User says \"forget 10:35\" → resolve to a timestamp range (that minute)\n2. Delete from `messages` where timestamp falls in that range\n3. Delete from `extracted_memories` where `source_timestamp` falls in that range\n4. Clean up FTS5 indexes (triggers handle this automatically)\n\nThe `source_timestamp` link is what makes this work — without it you'd have no way to know which extracted facts came from the forgotten conversation.\n\nIs that the direction you're thinking, or something different?\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> no-no.. have better genius idea lol. When an agent recalled a memory, and the user is satisfied with the result (so says, right or just continue the context etc.) - the agent could go back in the next xyxle immedietely and write a +1, -1 to the memory record. So we will see which memories are more inmactful and which are just noise.  How does it sound? ",
    "\n\nThat's a reinforcement signal on memories — basically implicit user feedback. When kiro recalls a fact and the user confirms it's useful (or corrects it), kiro bumps a score on that memory record.\n\nYou already have `emotion_score` on `extracted_memories`. This would be a second axis — call it `relevance_score` or `usefulness` — that tracks how often a recalled memory actually helped.\n\nOver time:\n- High-score memories get boosted in search ranking\n- Zero/negative-score memories are candidates for pruning during sleep\n- You get a natural signal for what matters vs noise, without the user explicitly managing memories\n\nThe tricky part is the feedback detection — how does kiro know the user was \"satisfied\"? Options:\n\n1. **Explicit** — kiro calls `agentbridge-store --boost --id 42` when the user confirms. Requires steering to teach kiro when to do this.\n2. **Implicit** — if the user continues the conversation without correcting, assume positive. If they say \"no that's wrong\" or correct, assume negative. This needs intent detection (you already have `IntentDetector`).\n\nOption 1 is simpler and more reliable. One new CLI flag, one column, done. The sleep prompt could also decay scores over time — memories that haven't been recalled in months fade naturally.\n\nHow do you want to handle the feedback signal — explicit tool call or implicit detection?\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> how about both?",
    "\n\nBoth works well — they complement each other:\n\n- **Explicit** (`agentbridge-store --boost/--demote --id 42`) — high confidence signal, kiro calls it when the user clearly confirms or rejects. Cheap to implement.\n- **Implicit** — lower confidence signal, smaller weight (e.g. +0.5 vs +1). Fires more often, catches the cases where the user doesn't explicitly react but the conversation flows naturally.\n\nThe implicit side could piggyback on the existing `IntentDetector` — add a \"memory confirmation\" pattern (user says \"yes\", \"exactly\", \"right\", continues on topic) and a \"memory rejection\" pattern (\"no\", \"that's wrong\", \"I never said that\"). When a recall happened in the last turn and the user responds with one of these, auto-boost/demote.\n\nSo the schema change is just one new column: `relevance_score INTEGER DEFAULT 0` on `extracted_memories`. Both paths write to the same column, just with different weights.\n\nWant me to add this to the LCM plan as a new stage, or build it now?\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> No, total different plan. and let's cont. the planning still. I also want track how often a memory piece is recalled (hit the search), feasible with simple wired logic?",
    "\n\nYes, very simple. Every time `searchExtracted()` returns results, bump a counter on each returned row:\n\n```sql\nUPDATE extracted_memories SET recall_count = recall_count + 1 WHERE id IN (?, ?, ?)\n```\n\nPure wired logic — no LLM involvement, no steering, no intent detection. Just a `recall_count INTEGER DEFAULT 0` column + one UPDATE after each search. The search functions already return the `id` of each result, so you have everything you need.\n\nCombined with the relevance score, you'd have two signals:\n- `recall_count` — how often this memory is retrieved (popularity/frequency)\n- `relevance_score` — whether it was actually useful when retrieved (quality)\n\nA memory with high recall_count but low/negative relevance_score = noise that keeps surfacing. Sleep could prune those. A memory with low recall_count but high relevance_score = rare but valuable — keep it.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> I think it will be powerful. How would you refine it?",
    "\n\nA few refinements:\n\n**Decay / time-weighting on recall_count.** A memory recalled 50 times 3 months ago but never since is stale. Instead of a raw counter, also track `last_recalled_at` timestamp. Sleep can then compute a weighted score: recent recalls matter more than old ones.\n\n**Don't count duplicate recalls in the same session.** If kiro searches \"dark mode\" 3 times in one conversation (rephrasing, retrying), that's one real recall, not three. Deduplicate by session — only bump once per memory per session. A simple in-memory `Set<\"memoryId:sessionId\">` in the search layer handles this without any DB overhead.\n\n**Separate L1 hits from L2 hits.** A memory found via L1 (raw message FTS) vs L2 (extracted fact FTS) tells you different things. The extracted memory's recall_count should only track when the extracted version itself was the one returned, not when the original raw message was found independently.\n\n**Relevance score weights:**\n- Explicit boost from kiro: +1 / -1\n- Implicit positive (user continues on topic): +0.3\n- Implicit negative (user corrects): -0.5\n- Asymmetric on purpose — one explicit rejection should outweigh a few implicit positives\n\n**Sleep-time actions based on signals:**\n- High recall + high relevance → promote to core knowledge (`memory.md`)\n- High recall + negative relevance → candidate for deletion or rewording\n- Zero recall after 30+ days → candidate for archival (not deletion — might be seasonal)\n- Log these decisions in the audit trail so you can review what sleep did and why\n\nThe minimal first step would be: `recall_count`, `last_recalled_at`, `relevance_score` — three columns, all wired logic except the relevance boost which needs one steering instruction. Everything else (decay, dedup, sleep actions) layers on top later.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> search the internet is teher any similar realozation, study, paper - where we could borrow idea?",
    "\n[Tool uses: web_search]",
    "\n[Tool uses: web_search]",
    "\n[Tool uses: web_search]",
    "\n[Tool uses: web_fetch]",
    "\n[Tool uses: web_fetch]",
    "Here's what I found:\n\nThere are several related approaches, and your idea sits at an interesting intersection:\n\n**Closest match: MemRL** ([arxiv.org/abs/2601.03192](https://arxiv.org/abs/2601.03192))\nStores past experiences as episodic memory and uses RL to learn which strategies work best. The key insight: it separates stable reasoning from flexible memory, letting agents improve without retraining weights. Your `relevance_score` is essentially a lightweight version of this — implicit RL signal from user feedback instead of formal policy optimization.\n\n**Mem-α** ([arxiv.org/abs/2509.25911](https://arxiv.org/html/2509.25911v1))\nThe most academically rigorous one. Uses 4 reward signals to train memory construction: correctness (does the memory help answer questions?), compression (is it compact?), tool format (did the write succeed?), and content quality (is it semantically valid?). Your `recall_count` maps to their correctness reward — memories that get recalled and confirmed are the ones that help answer questions. Their compression reward is interesting too — it penalizes bloated memory, which is what your sleep pruning of low-score memories would achieve.\n\n**Borrowable ideas:**\n\n1. **Compression reward from Mem-α** — during sleep, track the ratio of extracted memories to raw messages. If it's growing too fast (low compression), sleep should be more aggressive about merging/pruning. You could compute this as a simple metric: `extracted_count / message_count`.\n\n2. **Episodic vs semantic split from Mem-α** — they separate \"what happened\" (episodic) from \"what's true\" (semantic). You already have this implicitly: `messages` table = episodic, `extracted_memories` = semantic. The `recall_count` should weight these differently — a fact recalled 10 times is valuable, an episode recalled 10 times might mean it should be promoted to a fact.\n\n3. **Decay function from MemRL** — instead of raw `recall_count`, use a time-decayed score: `score = Σ(1 / (1 + days_since_recall))` for each recall event. Recent recalls contribute ~1.0, month-old recalls contribute ~0.03. This naturally handles the \"popular 3 months ago but stale now\" problem without needing a separate `last_recalled_at` field.\n\n4. **UMA's CRUD memory bank** — they support reorganize operations (merge two memories, split one). Your sleep could do this: if two extracted memories have high recall_count and similar content, merge them into a stronger single memory.\n\nThe bottom line: nobody has done exactly what you're proposing — wired recall counting + implicit/explicit user feedback scoring on extracted memories. The academic work uses RL training loops which require GPU clusters. Your approach is simpler and more practical: just count what gets used and let the user signal what's good. It's closer to a recommendation system's implicit feedback than to formal RL.\n\nReferences:\n[1] Mem-α: Learning Memory Construction via Reinforcement Learning - https://arxiv.org/html/2509.25911v1\n[2] 7 Emerging Memory Architectures for AI Agents - https://www.turingpost.com/p/agenticmemory\n[3] MemRL - https://arxiv.org/abs/2601.03192\n[4] Survey of AI Agent Memory Frameworks - https://www.graphlit.com/blog/survey-of-ai-agent-memory-frameworks\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> Thanks, exactly my broad thoughts that we should be maitianing these during sleep. So rank the 4 ideas: value - cost",
    "\n\n| # | Idea | Value | Cost | Verdict |\n|---|------|-------|------|---------|\n| 1 | **Recall count + time-decayed scoring** | High — gives sleep a concrete signal for what matters vs noise | Very low — one column, one UPDATE per search, decay formula in sleep prompt | **Do first** |\n| 2 | **Episodic→semantic promotion** | High — auto-surfaces patterns (\"recalled episode 10x = probably a fact\") | Low — sleep prompt instruction + check `recall_count` on messages table during sleep | **Do second** (just a prompt change once #1 exists) |\n| 3 | **Compression ratio metric** | Medium — tells you if extraction is bloating, but sleep already prunes | Near zero — one query: `extracted_count / message_count`, log it in audit | **Do alongside #1** (it's a one-liner) |\n| 4 | **Memory merge/reorganize during sleep** | Medium — deduplicates similar facts | Higher — needs similarity detection (FTS5 overlap or embedding cosine), merge logic, update FTS triggers | **Defer** — wait until you see actual duplicates in the data |\n\nSo: #1 + #3 now, #2 as a sleep prompt tweak after, #4 only if needed.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> Re 4. I think it is interesting and I dont wanna forget it (memory problems at humans LOL) -> why don't we run at the end of the sleep cycle another agentic loop where we can do it. Maybe only the merge it has better value - and slowly save space",
    "\n\nHa, fair point — let's not lose it to human memory decay.\n\nThe idea is solid: after the main sleep cycle (consolidation + extraction + pruning), run a second agentic pass that's purely about memory hygiene — find near-duplicate extracted memories and merge them. It's a natural fit because:\n\n- Sleep already has the LLM in the loop\n- The merge decision needs judgment (\"are these two facts really the same?\") — perfect for an LLM, overkill for wired logic\n- Running it at the end means it operates on already-clean data (post-pruning)\n- It's incremental — merge 5-10 pairs per cycle, not the whole DB at once\n\nThe sleep prompt would just get a new section at the end:\n\n```\n§7 Memory Merge (optional, time permitting)\nReview the top-N most-recalled extracted memories. If any two express \nthe same fact, merge them via agentbridge-store --merge --ids 42,67.\nThe merged record keeps the higher relevance_score and summed recall_count.\nLimit: max 5 merges per cycle.\n```\n\nThe `--merge` flag on agentbridge-store would: take two IDs, keep the newer one, combine scores, delete the older one. Simple wired logic behind an agentic decision.\n\nWant me to add all of this (#1 recall counting, #2 episodic promotion, #3 compression metric, #4 merge phase) to the LCM plan doc as a new stage? That way it's captured and we can implement in order.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> Add all but we cerated a new plan for all this new idea, not the LCM plan, what was it's name?",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "Only the LCM plan exists. You mentioned creating a new plan for these ideas — maybe you had a name in mind but we didn't get to create it yet? What would you like to call it?\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> give a cool name",
    "\n\nHow about **Memory Darwinism** — memories that get recalled and confirmed survive, the rest fade out. Natural selection for knowledge.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> Cool name, excelent. So provide the full plan",
    "\n[Tool uses: fs_write]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "Done (`db8c1ed`). 6 stages, 16 tasks, ordered by value/cost. Reminder: we have unpushed commits — run full tests before pushing.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> So practically we need 2 new field in the dbase, right?",
    "\n\nThree actually:\n\n1. `recall_count INTEGER DEFAULT 0` — how often it's been retrieved\n2. `last_recalled_at INTEGER` — timestamp of last retrieval (for decay calc)\n3. `relevance_score INTEGER DEFAULT 0` — user feedback signal (+1/-1 explicit, ±0.3/0.5 implicit)\n\nAll on `extracted_memories`. Want me to start implementing Stage 1?\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> if you add/s 0.3, 0.5 that it wont be an integer field",
    "\n\nGood catch. Two options:\n\n1. **Store as integer, multiply by 10** — explicit = +10/-10, implicit = +3/-5. Read time divides by 10. Keeps SQLite fast, avoids float weirdness.\n2. **Use REAL** — simpler code, but floats in SQLite are slightly messier for comparisons.\n\nI'd go with option 1 — integer scaled by 10. Same 3 columns, all INTEGER. Want me to proceed?\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> 1. is ok but I am still reviewing the plan. If you check again the found studies, anything else could be useful which can provide high value but not too resource consumpting usage?",
    "\n[Tool uses: thinking]",
    "Two more ideas worth stealing:\n\n**1. Search ranking boost from recall signals (zero cost)**\n\nRight now FTS5 ranks by text relevance only. Once you have `recall_count` and `relevance_score`, feed them back into the search ORDER BY:\n\n```sql\nORDER BY rank * (1 + 0.1 * recall_count) * CASE WHEN relevance_score > 0 THEN 1.2 ELSE 1.0 END\n```\n\nThis closes the Darwinism loop — memories that proved useful surface faster next time. It's just a SQL tweak in `searchExtracted()`, no new fields, no new code paths. Pure signal amplification.\n\n**2. Confidence at write time (one field, prompt-only cost)**\n\nFrom Mem-α's content quality reward: when kiro extracts a memory during sleep, it also rates its own confidence (1-5). \"User explicitly stated they prefer dark mode\" = 5. \"User might have implied they like TypeScript\" = 2.\n\nOne column: `confidence INTEGER DEFAULT 3`. Set during extraction via `agentbridge-store --confidence 4`. During recall, use as tiebreaker. During sleep fitness: low confidence + low recall = first to prune.\n\nCost is near zero — one field, one flag on the CLI, one line in the sleep prompt instruction.\n\n---\n\nSo the full picture would be 5 fields total on `extracted_memories`:\n\n| Field | Purpose | Set by |\n|-------|---------|--------|\n| `recall_count` | How often retrieved | Wired (search) |\n| `last_recalled_at` | When last retrieved | Wired (search) |\n| `relevance_score` | User feedback (×10 scaled) | Explicit CLI + implicit detection |\n| `confidence` | LLM self-assessed certainty at write time | Sleep prompt / agentbridge-store |\n\nPlus the search ranking boost which needs no fields at all.\n\nWant me to add these two to the plan?\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> excellent add these. I am think about the relevance feedback. I wouldnt give these on the fly, but into the 1st stage of sleep cycle: let's estabilish the explicit/implicit feedback duriung that time.",
    "\n\nSmart — batch the feedback during sleep instead of real-time detection. That way:\n\n- No IntentDetector extension needed (drop Task 7 entirely)\n- Sleep already has the full conversation history — it can review which memories were recalled and how the user reacted\n- One place to do all scoring, not scattered across live chat paths\n- The LLM is better at judging \"was this memory helpful?\" with full context than a regex pattern matcher in real-time\n\nSo the sleep cycle becomes:\n\n1. **§1 — Feedback pass**: Review today's conversations. For each recalled memory, check user's reaction → boost/demote via `agentbridge-store --boost/--demote`\n2. §2-§5 — Existing consolidation + extraction + pruning\n3. **§6 — Fitness review**: Use recall_count + relevance_score + confidence to promote/archive/prune\n4. **§7 — Merge pass**: Deduplicate near-similar memories\n\nLet me update the plan:\n[Tool uses: fs_write]",
