    "> I updated the darwinism plan, and added my comments starting with '?? '   let's dicusss each point 1by1 ",
    "\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "I see 4 comments. Let's go one by one.\n\n**1. \"§2-§5 — let's Inspect the order!\"**\n\nThe current sleep prompt phases — want me to pull up the actual `sleeping_prompt.md` so we can review the exact order and decide where the new phases slot in?\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> yes and let's review the whole thing with all new phases",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "Now I see the full picture. Here's the current order mapped against the proposed new phases:\n\n**Current sleep cycle:**\n1. §1 — Daily Summary (consolidation)\n2. §2 — Reminder & Todo Extraction\n3. §3 — Garbage Collection (the big one — 7 steps)\n4. §4 — Cron Verification\n5. §5 — Topic Reorg\n6. §6 — Disk Budget\n\n**Proposed new order with Darwinism phases:**\n\n| Phase | What | New? |\n|-------|------|------|\n| §1 — Feedback pass | Review recalled memories, boost/demote based on user reaction | NEW |\n| §2 — Daily Summary | Consolidation (daily/weekly/quarterly) | Existing §1 |\n| §3 — Reminder & Todo | Extract action items | Existing §2 |\n| §4 — Garbage Collection | The 7-step cleanup | Existing §3 |\n| §4 Step 6 update | Add `--confidence` to agentbridge-store calls | MODIFIED |\n| §5 — Cron Verification | Cross-check reminders vs crons | Existing §4 |\n| §6 — Topic Reorg | Stale topic review | Existing §5 |\n| §7 — Fitness Review | Promote/archive/prune based on recall+relevance signals | NEW |\n| §8 — Memory Merge | Deduplicate near-similar extracted memories (max 5) | NEW |\n| §9 — Disk Budget | Usage check | Existing §6 |\n\nFeedback runs first because it needs to score memories before GC might delete the conversations that provide context. Fitness + merge run last because they operate on the final state after all cleanup is done.\n\nDoes this ordering make sense, or do you want to shuffle anything? Then we'll move to your next comment.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> well sholudnt we push back 2.?? this is an llm compaction so it destroys the full chat from working dir, right?",
    "\n\nYou're right — the Daily Summary reads the raw transcripts and consolidates them into a summary `.md` file. If the Feedback pass needs to review today's conversations to judge user reactions to recalled memories, it needs those same raw transcripts.\n\nBut actually — the Daily Summary doesn't delete the transcripts. It reads the JSONL files and writes a summary, but the JSONL stays on disk. The working directory `.md` files also stay. So the raw data is still available after §2.\n\nThe real question is: does the Feedback pass need the full raw conversation, or can it work from the daily summary? \n\nI'd say it needs the raw conversation — the summary might not capture the nuance of \"user said 'exactly!' after a recall\" vs \"user corrected the recalled fact.\" So keeping Feedback first makes sense.\n\nBut there's no destructive step until GC (§4) starts deleting messages from the DB. So the order is safe as proposed — Feedback → Summary → GC. The transcripts survive all three.\n\nOr did you mean something else by \"destroys the full chat from working dir\"?\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> adding --confidence shouldnt be before this, or it works from teh database?",
    "\n\nGood catch. The `--confidence` flag is used during extraction (Step 6 of GC), where the LLM reads conversations and calls `agentbridge-store --confidence <1-5>` to save new extracted memories. That happens inside §4 (GC), not during the summary phase.\n\nThe Daily Summary (§2) doesn't extract memories — it just writes a prose summary `.md` file. So `--confidence` doesn't need to come before it.\n\nThe order is fine:\n\n1. §1 Feedback — scores existing memories (reads raw transcripts)\n2. §2 Daily Summary — writes consolidation files (reads raw transcripts)\n3. §4 GC Step 6 — extracts NEW memories with `--confidence` (reads raw transcripts + DB)\n\nAll three read from the same source (JSONL transcripts), none destroy it. The `--confidence` flag is only relevant at extraction time inside GC, which comes after both.\n\nReady for your next comment?\n[Tool uses: none]",
