    "\n[Tool uses: thinking]",
    "Your `??` #2 on Task 13:\n\n> \"doesnt it increase the dead weight if loaded into every context, do we need this, isnt it enough just to see the high ranking when selecting from the search?\"\n\nYou're right — promoting to `memory.md` is the wrong move. Here's why:\n\n**The problem with promotion to core knowledge:**\n- Core files (`memory.md`, `user_profile.md`, `agent_notes.md`) load into EVERY context, even when irrelevant\n- The same fact now lives in two places (extracted_memories + memory.md) — sync headache\n- More tokens burned per turn for diminishing returns\n\n**Search ranking already solves this:**\n- Stage 2 boosts high-recall + high-relevance memories in search results\n- They surface exactly when needed, not when they're not\n- Zero extra context weight on unrelated conversations\n\n**The only memories that belong in core files** are identity-level facts (\"user's name\", \"preferred language\", \"timezone\") — and those are already there by design via the agent's proactive writes to `user_profile.md`.\n\nMy recommendation: drop \"promote to core knowledge\" from the fitness review rules. Replace it with:\n\n```\n- High recall + high relevance → no action needed (search ranking handles it)\n```\n\nThe §6 fitness review then becomes purely about cleanup:\n- High recall + negative relevance → reword or delete\n- Zero recall after 60+ days → archive candidate  \n- Low confidence + low recall → first to prune\n\nAgree?\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> yes. We should be also pahsing out tottally the memory.md.. hm?",
