    "\n[Tool uses: grep]",
    "\n[Tool uses: fs_read]",
    "\n[Tool uses: grep]",
    "OK so here's the picture:\n\n**What exists today:**\n- `user_profile.md` — who the user is (agent writes proactively)\n- `agent_notes.md` — environment facts, lessons learned (agent writes proactively)\n- Both loaded via `readCoreKnowledge()` into context on session start + context assembly\n- No `memory.md` file — the Darwinism plan just used that as shorthand\n\n**The case for phasing them out:**\n- With Darwinism, the same facts live in `extracted_memories` with high recall/relevance scores\n- They surface via search when relevant, not burned into every turn\n- The agent's proactive writes are unreliable — LLM decides what's \"important\" without feedback signals\n- Two sources of truth for the same facts = drift\n\n**But — there's a real gap:**\n- `extracted_memories` requires a search query. On the very first message of a new session, there's no query yet — the agent doesn't know who it's talking to\n- `user_profile.md` gives the agent ambient identity: \"this is Kosal, speaks Hungarian, prefers minimal code\"\n- Without it, the first reply of every session would be generic until a search fires\n\n**My take:** don't phase out entirely, but shrink it to a tiny identity card — maybe 5-10 lines max, auto-generated from the top-ranked extracted memories during sleep. The agent stops writing to it directly. Sleep §7 (fitness review) regenerates it from the highest-scoring facts.\n\nThat way:\n- Minimal dead weight (~100 tokens instead of unbounded)\n- Always fresh (rebuilt from Darwinism signals, not LLM whims)\n- Covers the cold-start gap\n\nOr — even simpler — just keep `user_profile.md` as a manual ~5-line file you maintain yourself, and drop `agent_notes.md` entirely since those facts belong in extracted_memories.\n\nWhat's your instinct?\n[Tool uses: none]",
