    "> yep",
    "`??` #4 — Task 17:\n\n> \"if a raw message has been recalled 10+ times via L1 search, extract it as a permanent fact via agentbridge-store\"\n\nWhat this means:\n\nThe `messages` table holds raw user messages — noisy, conversational:\n> \"hey can you use that postgres connection string, it was something like host=10.0.1.5 port=5432 db=main\"\n\nIf this raw message keeps getting found by FTS5 search (because people keep asking about the DB connection), it means there's a valuable fact buried in conversational noise. But raw messages get pruned by max-messages limits and disk budget.\n\nThe idea: during sleep, if the agent notices a raw message has been hit 10+ times, it should extract the clean fact:\n> \"PostgreSQL connection: host=10.0.1.5, port=5432, db=main\"\n\n...via `agentbridge-store`, so it lives as a proper extracted_memory that survives pruning.\n\n**But honestly — I think this is redundant.** The MemoryExtractor already runs on every message and extracts facts. If a fact was worth extracting, it already got extracted. If it wasn't extracted, it's probably because it was conversational noise, not a fact.\n\nThe only edge case: the extractor missed something early on (before it was tuned well), and the raw message is the only record. But that's a historical artifact, not an ongoing problem.\n\nMy recommendation: **drop Task 17-18 entirely.** The extraction pipeline already handles this, and the Darwinism scoring on extracted_memories is the right place to invest. Chasing raw message recall counts adds complexity for a problem that barely exists.\n\nDrop it?\n[Tool uses: none]",
