memories get boosted, boosted memories rank higher next time.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> Opinion about this? If we would start again, would we use the same implementation?",
    "\n[Tool uses: thinking]",
    "Honest take — I'd keep the core architecture but change the cascade order and trim the fat:\n\n**What's right (would keep):**\n- Agent-driven recall — LLM decides when/what to search, not the bridge. This is the best design decision in the whole system.\n- SQLite + FTS5 — fast, local, zero dependencies, good enough for the scale\n- Dual-language FTS5 — solves the real Hungarian/English problem\n- JSONL as append-only source of truth\n- Sleep cycle for maintenance\n- Darwinism concept fits naturally on top\n\n**What I'd change:**\n\n1. **Flip the search order.** This is the biggest one. Right now extracted memories are stages 5-6, after 4 stages of raw message search. But extracted memories are the *clean signal* — curated facts, deduplicated, scored. Raw messages are noisy (\"hey can you check that thing\"). I'd search extracted memories first, raw messages as fallback only when extracted returns nothing.\n\n2. **Short-circuit on confidence.** If stage 1 returns 10+ high-quality hits, skip the remaining 7 stages. Currently all 8 run every time regardless.\n\n3. **Consolidation summaries belong in the DB.** Stage 7 greps markdown files — no ranking, no scoring, just keyword presence. If starting fresh, I'd store summaries in a `consolidations` FTS5 table instead of flat files. (Ironic — we just removed the compactions table, but the *concept* of searchable summaries in SQLite was right, the implementation was wrong.)\n\n4. **4-5 stages, not 8.** Stages 1-4 are all variations of \"search raw messages slightly differently.\" In practice, relaxed FTS5 catches most of what strict FTS5 misses. The two LIKE stages are expensive and rarely add unique results.\n\n**What I wouldn't bother changing:**\n- CLI via execute_bash — it's a transport constraint, not a design flaw\n- Temporal decay as post-hoc multiplier — moving it into SQL adds complexity for marginal gain\n- No vector search in main path — FTS5 + keyword covers 95% of cases, embeddings add latency and a model dependency\n\nThe TL;DR: the cascade was built bottom-up (each stage added to fix a real miss), but if designed top-down, you'd start with extracted memories and work outward. The Darwinism scoring makes this reorder even more compelling — the best-scored memories should be searched first.\n\nWorth adding this as a future refactor item, or leave it for now?\n[Tool uses: none]",
