    "Studied the LCM memory research docs. Here's how they handle provenance:\n\n**LCM's approach:**\n- Each recalled fact includes `source: memory/2025-11-27.md#L12` — file path + line number\n- Used for two things:\n  1. **Citation in recall** — agent can verify/expand by reading the source\n  2. **Evidence linking in Reflect** — when updating opinions/beliefs, trace back to supporting/contradicting facts\n\n**Our equivalent:**\n- `source_message_ids: \"451,452,453\"` — DB row IDs instead of file+line\n- Same two uses: recall output shows `source_ids`, sleep §1 can trace back for feedback\n\n**We're at parity on source linking.** Nothing else to wire.\n\n**One LCM concept we DON'T have** (but it's separate from message IDs):\n- **Entity linking** — they tag every fact with `@Peter`, `@warelay` etc, and maintain per-entity pages (`bank/entities/Peter.md`). This enables \"tell me about Peter\" queries via entity filter, not just keyword search. Could be a future enhancement but it's a different feature entirely.\n\nBottom line: source_message_ids implementation is complete. Write path, read path, sleep feedback path — all wired.\n[Tool uses: none]",
