    "> we changed the dbase structure adding new fields, existing system will pick this up or we need workaround?",
    "\n\nThe existing system will pick it up automatically — no workaround needed. Here's why:\n\nThe migrations in `memory-manager.ts` `initialize()` are **idempotent**:\n\n```typescript\nfor (const ddl of [\n  \"ALTER TABLE extracted_memories ADD COLUMN recall_count INTEGER DEFAULT 0\",\n  \"ALTER TABLE extracted_memories ADD COLUMN last_recalled_at INTEGER\",\n  ...\n]) {\n  try { this.db.exec(ddl); } catch { /* already exists */ }\n}\n```\n\n- **Fresh DB**: columns get created\n- **Existing DB**: ALTER TABLE throws \"duplicate column name\" → caught and ignored\n- **All existing rows**: get the DEFAULT values (recall_count=0, relevance_score=0, confidence=3, source_message_ids=NULL)\n\nThe only thing needed is a **rebuild + deploy**:\n\n```bash\n./scripts/deploy.sh\n```\n\nThis compiles the new code and copies it to `~/.agentbridge/`. Next time the bridge starts (or the sleep agent runs), `initialize()` runs the migrations and the new columns appear on the existing table with correct defaults.\n\nNo data loss, no manual SQL, no downtime.\n[Tool uses: none]",
