    "Here's what's left:\n\n**Future Ideas** (from Memory.asbuilt):\n1. Archive DB layer — move zero-recall 60+ day memories to a separate SQLite archive\n2. Entity linking — tag memories with entity mentions, per-entity summary pages\n3. AES encryption for restricted (classification=3) memories at rest\n\n**Major refactor** — Recall Cascade Refactor (`docs/TODO/recall-cascade-refactor.md`):\n- Flip the 8-stage cascade to 5 stages, extracted memories first (they have Darwinism scores now), raw messages as fallback\n- Merge strict+relaxed FTS5 into one query\n- Drop the expensive LIKE substring stages (3-4)\n- Move consolidation search from file grep to FTS5 table\n- Short-circuit when extracted memories return enough high-scoring results\n\nThat refactor was explicitly marked \"implement after Darwinism is live and generating data\" — so it makes sense to let it run for a while, collect recall_count/relevance data, then validate which stages actually contribute before cutting them.\n\n**Also still open**: Phase 3 — Intelligence (proactive recall, importance scoring, contradiction detection) but that's a bigger design effort.\n\nWant to push + deploy first, then tackle one of these?\n[Tool uses: none]",
