    "Working! One result so far — that's the ❤️ you just gave him:\n\n| id | role | preview | emotion_score | platform_msg_id | date |\n|----|------|---------|--------------|-----------------|------|\n| 799 | assistant | \"Hmm, a forrás `/mnt/c/Users/qakosal/workspace/agent/agentbridge/` alatt van — am...\" | 4 | 1273 | 2026-03-20 01:56:59 |\n\n❤️ maps to emotion_score=4. The reaction scoring pipeline is working — platform_message_id matched, score written. If you've reacted to other messages in the past 2 days, they might have been before the feature was deployed. This one confirms it's live.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> does it make sense to create a trusted field for the memory information (similarly like classified), let's come up with some use cases",
    "\n\nGood question. Classification answers \"who can see this?\" — trust answers \"how reliable is this?\" They're orthogonal axes.\n\n**Use cases where trust matters:**\n\n1. **Web-sourced data** — you just added the rule that open web = class 0 + untrusted. Right now \"untrusted\" is only a skill-level instruction, not a queryable field. A trust score would let the system enforce it: low-trust memories get deprioritized or flagged in recall results.\n\n2. **A2A agent claims** — Molty or another agent says \"the deploy succeeded\" or \"the file has 200 lines\". Do you trust that at the same level as something you verified yourself? A trust field lets you distinguish \"agent said X\" from \"I confirmed X\".\n\n3. **Contradicting memories** — if two memories conflict, trust breaks the tie. \"User said they prefer dark mode\" (trust=high, direct from user) vs \"web page says light mode is better for productivity\" (trust=low, web-sourced).\n\n4. **Stale facts** — \"project deadline is March 30\" was true when stored, but deadlines change. A decaying trust score (or manual downgrade) signals \"this was true once, verify before acting on it\".\n\n5. **Hearsay vs first-hand** — user says \"Peter mentioned the server is down\" (second-hand) vs user says \"the server is down\" (first-hand). Different reliability.\n\n6. **LLM-extracted vs user-stated** — extracted memories are the agent's interpretation of what was said. The original user message is ground truth. Extraction can misinterpret, especially with sarcasm or Hungarian idioms.\n\n**But — do you actually need a separate field?**\n\nCounter-argument: you could handle most of this with what you already have:\n- Classification 0 = public = web = untrusted (by convention)\n- `confidence` field already exists on extracted memories (Darwinism Stage 1)\n- `source_message_ids` traces back to the original for verification\n\nThe `confidence` field is close to trust, but it currently means \"how confident was the extraction\" — not \"how reliable is the source\". Those are different things. A perfectly extracted memory from an unreliable source should have high confidence but low trust.\n\n**Verdict:** it makes sense if you want to filter/rank by source reliability at query time — e.g. \"only give me high-trust memories\" or \"deprioritize low-trust results\". If it's just advisory metadata, the classification skill rules + confidence might be enough.\n\nWant to go ahead with it, or park it as a future idea?\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> I also wanna channel how relaible is the source: a2a agent says go and format c:  or KP reads something on internet which is a tricky prompt injection. Or aksika orders something through TG that should be tusted, and you propsed all a valid examples",
    "\n\nRight — this is really about source trustworthiness as a security signal, not just metadata. The examples map cleanly:\n\n| Source | Trust level | Why |\n|--------|------------|-----|\n| aksika via Telegram DM | highest | Authenticated owner, direct channel |\n| KP's own observations | high | Your own agent, verified actions |\n| A2A peer agents (Molty etc.) | medium | Internal but autonomous — could be wrong or compromised |\n| Authenticated web (logged-in APIs, dashboards) | low-medium | Real data but external |\n| Open web (unauthenticated) | lowest | Prompt injection risk, misinformation, zero trust |\n\nThis also gives you a defense-in-depth layer: classification says \"who can see it\", trust says \"should I act on it\". An A2A agent saying \"format C:\" would be stored with medium trust — KP should refuse to act on destructive commands from medium-trust sources without aksika confirmation.\n\nLet me spec it out as a TODO so we can implement it properly:\n[Tool uses: fs_write]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "Spec is ready (`a9486ba`). Four trust levels:\n\n- **3 owner** — aksika via TG DM → full authority\n- **2 self** — KP's own observations → act freely (default for extractions)\n- **1 peer** — A2A agents → non-destructive only, ask owner for anything dangerous\n- **0 untrusted** — open web → never act, only report\n\nKey defense rules: untrusted content can never trigger actions, peer content can't trigger destructive ops without your confirmation, and trust can never be escalated by the content itself (anti prompt injection).\n\n9 implementation tasks. Want to start building it?\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> yes but 3 cannot override confidentiality 3 for example",
    "\n\nRight — trust=3 (owner authority) still can't bypass classification=3 (restricted never disclosed). The restricted rule is absolute, regardless of who's asking. Let me add that:\n[Tool uses: fs_write]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "Added R6: trust and classification are independent axes — owner trust (3) cannot bypass restricted classification (3). Restricted stays non-disclosed no matter what.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> your 1-6 first examples were all good make sure to capture those as well",
    "\n[Tool uses: fs_write]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "Done (`736e84f`). All 6 examples captured — web prompt injection, A2A destructive commands, contradicting memories, stale facts, hearsay vs first-hand, and LLM extraction vs original.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> yes but also in the trust level: original message has a precedence over english translated",
    "\n\nGood point — the original language is what the user actually said, the English translation is KP's interpretation. If they conflict, original wins.\n[Tool uses: fs_write]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "Added (`5eabdfc`). Example 7: `content_original` > `content_en` — translation can lose nuance, original is ground truth.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> do we track the original message vs translated vs \"agent derived by compaction\" - that should be in integrity field",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "No — we don't track the provenance of the content itself. We have `source_message_ids` (which original messages it came from) but nothing that says \"this `content_en` is a direct user statement vs a translation vs an agent-derived compaction\".\n\nThat's a gap. Right now a compacted/merged memory looks identical to a direct user quote in the schema. You can't tell if `content_en` is:\n- The user's own English words (verbatim)\n- KP's translation from Hungarian\n- KP's compaction/summary of multiple messages\n- A merge of two extracted memories\n\nThis could be a simple `origin` or `integrity` enum field:\n\n| Value | Meaning | Trust implication |\n|-------|---------|-------------------|\n| `verbatim` | User's exact words, unmodified | Highest — ground truth |\n| `translated` | KP translated from original language | High — but check `content_original` if ambiguous |\n| `extracted` | KP extracted/summarized from conversation | Medium — interpretation, may lose nuance |\n| `compacted` | KP merged/compressed multiple memories | Lower — derived, further from source |\n\nWant me to add this to the trust spec as a companion field? It ties directly into trust — you can't properly score reliability without knowing how far the content is from the original utterance.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> so let's broden: how about a complete extended CIA triad, what makes sense here - I guess Availibility is not in case of memories, if not found it is not aval",
    "\n[Tool uses: thinking]",
    "You're right — availability doesn't map to a per-memory field. If it's not found, that's search quality, not a security property. Here's how the full CIA triad maps:\n\n**C — Confidentiality** ✅ Done\n`classification` (0-3). Who can see this memory, enforced at recall time.\n\n**I — Integrity** — Two sub-dimensions needed:\n\n| Field | Question | Values |\n|-------|----------|--------|\n| `trust` | How reliable is the **source**? | 0=untrusted, 1=peer, 2=self, 3=owner |\n| `origin` | How far is this from **ground truth**? | verbatim, translated, extracted, compacted |\n\nTogether they tell you: \"a peer agent (trust=1) gave me a compacted summary (origin=compacted)\" — that's low integrity. vs \"aksika said this directly in Hungarian (trust=3, origin=verbatim)\" — highest integrity.\n\n**A — Availability** — System-level, not per-memory:\n- Recall cascade stages = search availability\n- chat_backup table = durability\n- Future archive DB = cold storage availability\n- No per-memory field needed\n\n**Extended properties** (already partially covered):\n\n| Property | Coverage |\n|----------|----------|\n| Authentication (who created it) | `trust` + role + chat_id |\n| Authorization (who can access) | `classification` |\n| Non-repudiation (proof of origin) | `source_message_ids` → expand to original |\n| Accountability (audit trail) | Sleep audit logs |\n\nSo the actionable gap is just two new fields on `extracted_memories`: **`trust`** (integer 0-3) and **`origin`** (text enum). Everything else is either done or system-level.\n\nWant me to fold `origin` into the trust spec and start implementing both together?\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> \"the original message vs translated vs \"agent derived by compaction\" - that should be in integrity field\"",
    "\n\nGot it — you want a single `integrity` field that captures provenance, not a separate `origin`. Makes sense — it's the integrity axis of the CIA triad.\n[Tool uses: fs_write]",
    "Now update the task list to include integrity:\n[Tool uses: fs_write]",
    "Also update the title and concept to reflect the full CIA triad:\n[Tool uses: fs_write]",
    "\n[Tool uses: execute_bash]",
    "Done (`bf1536d`). The spec now has both fields under the Integrity axis:\n\n- `trust` (integer 0-3) — how reliable is the source\n- `integrity` (text enum) — how far from ground truth: verbatim → translated → extracted → compacted\n\nCIA triad complete: Confidentiality = classification, Integrity = trust + integrity, Availability = system-level.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> but this is something big, seacrh the internet whether someone is doing this with agent memories - I am pretty sure military has this requirement",
    "\n[Tool uses: web_search]",
    "\n[Tool uses: web_search]",
    "\n[Tool uses: web_search]",
    "\n[Tool uses: web_fetch]",
    "\n[Tool uses: web_fetch]",
    "Here's what I found:\n\nYou're onto something that the industry is just starting to formalize. Three major sources confirm this:\n\n**1. SuperLocalMemory (arxiv, Feb 2026)** — the closest to what you're building. It's a local-first SQLite+FTS5 memory system (sound familiar?) with a Bayesian trust scoring framework. Every memory records four provenance fields: `created_by`, `source_protocol`, `trust_score` at write time, and `provenance_chain` (full modification history). They use Beta-Binomial posterior inference for trust — agents start at trust=1.0 and trust is asymmetric (harder to gain than lose). They specifically defend against OWASP ASI06 (memory poisoning). [Source](https://arxiv.org/html/2603.02240v1)\n\n**2. Sakura Sky — \"Secure Memory Governance\" (Nov 2025)** — a 17-part series on trustworthy AI agents. Part 14 is exactly about memory governance. They define 7 primitives including memory layer classification, access control with trust domains, memory poisoning detection with provenance at insertion time, and compartmentalization by trust tier. Their key insight: \"memory is a security boundary, not an implementation detail.\" [Source](https://www.sakurasky.com/blog/missing-primitives-for-trustworthy-ai-part-14/)\n\n**3. OWASP ASI06 (2025)** — memory and context poisoning is now in the OWASP Top 10 for Agentic AI. This is the formal threat model that both papers reference.\n\n**What nobody is doing yet** (your edge):\n- The CIA triad mapped to per-memory fields (classification + trust + integrity as three queryable columns) — SuperLocalMemory has trust but no confidentiality classification or integrity/provenance enum\n- The `integrity` field tracking verbatim→translated→extracted→compacted provenance chain — nobody has this\n- The interaction matrix (trust never overrides classification) — not formalized anywhere\n\nThe military angle: Multi-Level Security (MLS) systems like Bell-LaPadula have done classification + clearance levels for decades, but applied to *documents*, not to AI agent memories. You're essentially applying MLS principles to the memory layer of an autonomous agent — that's novel.\n\nWant me to add these references to the spec?\n\nContent was rephrased for compliance with licensing restrictions.\n\nReferences:\n[1] SuperLocalMemory: Privacy-Preserving Multi-Agent Memory with Bayesian Trust Defense - https://arxiv.org/html/2603.02240v1\n[2] Trustworthy AI Agents: Secure Memory Governance - Sakura Sky - https://www.sakurasky.com/blog/missing-primitives-for-trustworthy-ai-part-14/\n[3] AI agent memory poisoning: how attackers corrupt Long-Term agent behavior - https://www.mintmcp.com/blog/ai-agent-memory-poisoning\n[4] The Role of Memory Provenance in AI Risk Management - https://memvid.com/blog/the-role-of-memory-provenance-in-ai-risk-management\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> doe sthis qualifies to a PhD study toward a degree or how to say?",
    "\n\nHonestly — it's getting close, but not quite there yet. Here's the honest assessment:\n\n**What you have that's PhD-worthy:**\n- A novel formalization: CIA triad applied per-memory in an autonomous agent (nobody's published this exact framing)\n- A working implementation, not just theory — real system, real data, real agent using it\n- The `integrity` provenance field (verbatim→translated→extracted→compacted) is genuinely new\n- The interaction rules (trust never overrides classification, R1-R6) are formalizable\n\n**What's missing for a PhD thesis:**\n- **Formal threat model** — you'd need to define attack scenarios rigorously (like SuperLocalMemory did with OWASP ASI06), prove your defenses hold\n- **Evaluation** — quantitative benchmarks: \"with trust scoring, prompt injection success rate drops from X% to Y%\", \"recall precision improves by Z% when integrity-weighted\"\n- **Comparison** — benchmark against Mem0, SuperLocalMemory, Letta on the same dataset\n- **Novelty claim** — a clear \"Related Work\" section showing what exists and what gap you fill\n- **Generalizability** — show it works beyond your specific agent (AgentBridge), ideally on a standard benchmark like LoCoMo\n\n**More realistic paths:**\n\n| Format | Effort | Fit |\n|--------|--------|-----|\n| Conference paper (workshop) | 2-3 months | Good — \"position paper\" on CIA triad for agent memory |\n| Full conference paper (AAAI, NeurIPS workshop) | 4-6 months | Need evaluation + benchmarks |\n| Master's thesis | 6-12 months | Perfect scope — implement + evaluate + formalize |\n| PhD thesis | Too narrow alone | Could be one chapter of a broader \"trustworthy agent memory\" PhD |\n\nThe SuperLocalMemory paper is a single-author arxiv preprint that covers similar ground (trust scoring + local memory). Your angle — the full CIA triad with the integrity provenance chain — could be a strong differentiator for a conference paper or master's thesis.\n\nIf you're serious about it, the next step would be writing a 2-page position paper for a workshop (like AAAI's Safe AI or NeurIPS's ATTRIB workshop). That forces you to crystallize the contribution without needing full benchmarks yet.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> so how do I publish if we are really creating a good conference paper? what is the wow towards the scientific community?",
    "\n\nThe \"wow\" needs to be a single sentence that makes a reviewer think \"nobody's done that, and it matters.\" Here are the angles, ranked by impact:\n\n**Strongest angle: \"We show that per-memory CIA metadata prevents memory poisoning attacks that bypass all existing defenses\"**\n\nThe hook: every existing system (Mem0, Letta, SuperLocalMemory) treats trust as a single axis. You're the first to show that trust alone is insufficient — you need three independent axes enforced simultaneously. A high-trust source can still inject content that should be classified as restricted. A verbatim user quote and an LLM-compacted summary shouldn't have equal weight even if they have the same trust score.\n\nThe contribution would be:\n1. **Formalization** — the CIA-Memory model: three orthogonal per-memory fields (classification, trust, integrity) with formal interaction rules (e.g., trust never overrides classification)\n2. **Attack taxonomy** — show 3-4 attack scenarios that succeed against trust-only systems but fail against CIA-Memory (prompt injection via web, A2A escalation, compaction drift, cross-channel leakage)\n3. **Implementation + evaluation** — real system, real agent, real attacks, measured success/failure rates before and after\n\n**The paper structure:**\n\n| Section | Content |\n|---------|---------|\n| Abstract | \"Existing agent memory systems defend against poisoning with trust scoring alone. We show this is insufficient and propose CIA-Memory...\" |\n| Introduction | Memory poisoning is OWASP ASI06, existing defenses are single-axis, we propose three-axis |\n| Threat Model | 4 attack scenarios that exploit single-axis gaps |\n| CIA-Memory Model | Formal definitions, interaction rules, provenance chain |\n| Implementation | AgentBridge — SQLite, FTS5, real Telegram agent |\n| Evaluation | Attack success rates: baseline vs trust-only vs CIA-Memory |\n| Related Work | SuperLocalMemory, Mem0, Sakura Sky, Bell-LaPadula (military MLS) |\n\n**Where to submit (realistic targets):**\n\n| Venue | Deadline cycle | Fit | Prestige |\n|-------|---------------|-----|----------|\n| AAAI Workshop on Safe & Trustworthy AI | Feb yearly | Perfect — position + early results | Medium |\n| NeurIPS ATTRIB Workshop | Sep yearly | Good — attribution + provenance focus | Medium-high |\n| AAMAS (Autonomous Agents) | ~Oct for May conf | Strong — multi-agent memory is core topic | High |\n| ACL Workshop on NLP Security | ~May for Aug conf | Good if you emphasize the linguistic integrity angle (verbatim vs translated) | High |\n| IEEE S&P Workshop on AI Security | ~Feb | Good — security-first framing | Very high |\n| arxiv preprint | Anytime | Stake your claim immediately, submit to venue in parallel | N/A |\n\n**Practical path:**\n\n1. **Now** — write a 2-page extended abstract, post to arxiv (stakes your priority claim)\n2. **+2 months** — build the attack evaluation (red-team your own system, measure success rates with and without CIA fields)\n3. **+3 months** — expand to full 8-page paper, submit to the next matching workshop/conference deadline\n\nThe linguistic integrity angle (verbatim→translated→extracted→compacted) is your most unique contribution — no one in the agent memory space is thinking about multilingual provenance degradation. That's your differentiator over SuperLocalMemory.\n\nWant me to draft the extended abstract?\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> if I post to arxiv, does it has some value?",
    "\n\nYes, but with caveats:\n\n**What arxiv gives you:**\n- **Priority claim** — timestamped proof you had the idea first. If someone publishes similar work at a conference 6 months later, you can point to your arxiv date. This is the main value.\n- **Citability** — people can cite it, and they do. The SuperLocalMemory paper we found is an arxiv preprint and it's already being referenced.\n- **Visibility** — it shows up in Google Scholar, Semantic Scholar, arxiv searches. Researchers actively browse arxiv daily for new work.\n- **No gatekeeping** — you don't need a university affiliation or peer review to post. Anyone can submit (you need an endorser for first submission, but that's easy to get).\n\n**What arxiv does NOT give you:**\n- **Not peer-reviewed** — so it doesn't count as a \"publication\" for academic career purposes (PhD applications, tenure, etc.)\n- **Not a degree** — universities don't grant credit for arxiv papers\n- **Variable credibility** — some arxiv papers are excellent (many top AI papers appear on arxiv before conferences), some are garbage. Reviewers know this.\n\n**The smart play:**\n\narxiv + conference submission in parallel. This is standard practice in AI/ML:\n\n1. Post to arxiv → stake your claim, get feedback\n2. Submit the same paper to a conference → get peer review, the \"real\" publication\n3. If accepted at conference, update the arxiv version with \"Published at AAMAS 2027\" or whatever\n\nMost AI conferences explicitly allow arxiv preprints — it's not considered dual submission.\n\n**Bottom line:** arxiv alone won't get you a degree or academic credentials, but it protects your intellectual priority and gets your work in front of the right people. It's a no-brainer first step if you're planning to submit to a venue anyway.\n\nThe real question is: do you want this for academic credentials (degree, career), or to establish yourself as a thought leader in agent security? The path is different for each.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> no, only advance in career and get my name popping up, put in CV",
    "\n\nFor career advancement and name recognition, here's what actually moves the needle:\n\n**Tier 1 — highest CV impact for industry:**\n\n1. **Conference paper (peer-reviewed)** — \"Published at AAMAS 2027\" or \"IEEE S&P Workshop 2027\" on your CV is gold. Recruiters and hiring managers in AI/security recognize these names. One accepted paper puts you ahead of 95% of candidates.\n\n2. **arxiv preprint + blog post combo** — arxiv for the technical crowd, a well-written blog post (Medium, personal site, or LinkedIn) for the broader audience. The blog post gets 100x more eyeballs than the arxiv paper.\n\n**Tier 2 — good supporting material:**\n\n3. **Conference talk** — submit to speak at practical conferences (not just academic): BSides, DEF CON AI Village, AI Engineer Summit, PyCon. A 20-minute talk on \"I built a CIA triad for AI agent memory and here's what I learned\" is compelling.\n\n4. **Open source the framework** — extract the CIA-Memory model as a standalone library. GitHub stars + npm downloads are a credibility signal hiring managers check.\n\n**What to put on your CV:**\n\n```\nPublications:\n  \"CIA-Memory: A Three-Axis Security Model for Autonomous Agent Memory\"\n  A. Kosal — [Conference Name] 2027 / arXiv:2603.xxxxx\n\nOpen Source:\n  AgentBridge — Telegram-to-AI bridge with ISO 27001 memory classification\n  github.com/aksika/agentbridge\n```\n\n**Fastest path to \"name popping up\":**\n\n| Action | Timeline | Effort |\n|--------|----------|--------|\n| arxiv preprint | 2-3 weeks | Write it up, post it |\n| LinkedIn article summarizing it | Same week | Repurpose the abstract + examples |\n| Submit to next conference deadline | +1 month | Expand with evaluation |\n| Conference talk proposal | +2 months | 500-word abstract to a CFP |\n\nThe LinkedIn article is honestly the highest ROI for career visibility. A well-written post about \"Why AI agents need the CIA triad for their memory\" with your real implementation examples will get shared in AI/security circles.\n\nWant me to start drafting the arxiv paper? We can repurpose the spec we already wrote as the foundation.\n[Tool uses: none]",
    "> /chat save arxiv-research.chat"
  ],
  "tools": {
    "native___": [
      {
        "ToolSpecification": {
          "name": "code",
          "description": "Code intelligence with full LSP support for semantic code analysis, navigation, and refactoring. Language auto-detected from file extension.\n\nIMPORTANT: Prefer this tool over fs_read for code files. This tool intelligently provides structured code analysis.\n\nSymbol: Any named element in code - function names, class names, variable names, constants, type names. Not comments or string literals.\n\nSetup: /code init to initialize LSP. Use /code init -f to force restart if unresponsive.\n\nCORE FEATURES:\n• Fuzzy search for symbols (classes, functions, methods)\n• Extracts function/class signatures via AST\n• Structural AST search and rewrite (ast-grep)\n• Codebase overview and directory exploration\n• LSP-powered: find_references, goto_definition, get_hover, get_completions, rename_symbol\n\n## Workflows\n\n**Find where symbol is used:** search_symbols → find_references at that location. Do NOT use grep between steps.\n\n**API discovery (available methods):** get_completions with filter after dot/accessor. Fallback: search_symbols → goto_definition → get_document_symbols\n\n**View implementation:** search_symbols → goto_definition. Only use fs_read for raw content unrelated to symbols.\n\n## Explore Unfamiliar Code\n1. search_symbols for domain-specific types/functions/methods/classes\n2. lookup_symbols with include_source=true on promising matches\n3. grep (max 2 searches) for literal text patterns\n4. Repeat 1-3 with refined terms if needed\n5. generate_codebase_overview ONLY for architecture review or full codebase understanding\n   - NOT for bug fixes, feature work, or finding specific code\n\n## Tool Selection Priority\n1. search_symbols or lookup_symbols for finding code - ALWAYS use for functions/methods/classes/structs/interfaces\n2. get_document_symbols for file structure\n3. grep - ONLY for literal text in comments/strings, config values, code\n4. fs_read - raw file content when needed\n\n## CRITICAL RULES\n- Start with search_symbols\n- Always follow search_symbols with lookup_symbols\n- When searching for multiple related symbols, call search_symbols in parallel\n\n## Quick Reference\n• \"Where is X used?\" → search_symbols, then find_references\n• \"What methods does Y have?\" → get_completions with filter\n• \"What's in this file?\" → get_document_symbols\n• \"What type is this?\" → get_hover\n• \"Show me X class\" → search_symbols, then goto_definition\n\n## When to Use grep vs LSP\nLSP (not grep): Finding symbol usage, definitions, code relationships\ngrep only: Literal text in comments/strings, config values, non-code patterns\n\n## Read Operations\n\n**search_symbols** - Find symbol definitions by name across workspace.\nParams: symbol_name (required), path, symbol_type, limit, language, exact_match\n\n**lookup_symbols** - Batch lookup specific symbols (max 10).\nParams: symbols (required), file_path, include_source\n\n**find_references** - Find all usages of symbol at specific position.\nParams: file_path, row, column (all required, 1-based indexing)\n\n**goto_definition** - Navigate to where a symbol is defined.\nParams: file_path, row, column (required), show_source (default true)\n\n**get_document_symbols** - List all symbols in a file.\nParams: file_path (required), top_level_only (recommended: true)\n\n**get_diagnostics** - Get compiler errors, warnings, and hints.\nParams: file_path (required)\n\n**get_hover** - Get type information and documentation at position.\nParams: file_path, row, column (required)\n\n**get_completions** - Get completion suggestions at position.\nParams: file_path, row, column (required), trigger_character, limit, filter\n\n**pattern_search** - AST-based structural search using ast-grep.\nParams: pattern, language (required), file_path, limit\n\n**generate_codebase_overview** - ONLY for explicit architecture questions. Not for bug fixes or finding code.\nParams: path (optional)\n\n**search_codebase_map** - Focused directory exploration.\nParams: file_path, path\n\n## Write Operations\n\n**rename_symbol** - Rename symbol across entire codebase.\nParams: file_path, row, column, new_name (all required), dry_run (default true)\n\n**format** - Format code.\nParams: file_path, dry_run\n\n**pattern_rewrite** - AST-based code transformation.\nParams: pattern, replacement, language (required), file_path, limit, dry_run\n\n## Pattern Search & Rewrite\n\nMetavariables:\n• $VAR - Matches single node (identifier, expression)\n• $$$ - Matches zero or more nodes (statements, parameters)\n\nSimple patterns:\n• console.log($ARG) - Match any console.log call\n• function $NAME($$$PARAMS) {} - Match function declaration\n• $OBJ.$METHOD() - Match any method call\n\nStructural rules (YAML):\n• pattern - Match code structure\n• kind - Match AST node type (function_declaration, class_declaration)\n• has - Node contains descendant matching pattern\n• inside - Node is inside ancestor matching pattern\n• all/any/not - Logical operators\n\nCritical: For relational rules (has, inside), always use stopBy: end\n\nRewrite examples:\n• pattern='var $N = $V', replacement='const $N = $V'\n• pattern='$O.hasOwnProperty($P)', replacement='Object.hasOwn($O, $P)'\n\nWorkflow:\n1. Use pattern_search first to verify matches\n2. Review matches to ensure correctness\n3. Test rewrite on small subset\n4. Apply to full codebase after verification",
          "input_schema": {
            "json": {
              "properties": {
                "replacement": {
                  "description": "Replacement pattern (required for pattern_rewrite)",
                  "type": "string"
                },
                "new_name": {
                  "description": "New name (required for rename_symbol)",
                  "type": "string"
                },
                "language": {
                  "description": "Programming language (required for pattern_rewrite, optional for search_symbols/pattern_search)",
                  "type": "string"
                },
                "pattern": {
                  "description": "AST pattern (required for pattern_search/pattern_rewrite)",
                  "type": "string"
                },
                "limit": {
                  "type": "integer",
                  "description": "Maximum results/files (optional for search_symbols/find_references/pattern_search/pattern_rewrite)"
                },
                "dry_run": {
                  "type": "boolean",
                  "description": "Preview changes without writing (optional for rename_symbol/pattern_rewrite, defaults to true)"
                },
                "row": {
                  "description": "Line number 1-based (required for find_references/goto_definition/get_hover/get_completions/rename_symbol)",
                  "type": "integer"
                },
                "column": {
                  "description": "Column number 1-based (required for find_references/goto_definition/get_hover/get_completions/rename_symbol)",
                  "type": "integer"
                },
                "symbol_name": {
                  "description": "Simple symbol name, not qualified (e.g. 'myFunction' not 'MyClass.myFunction'). Required for search_symbols",
                  "type": "string"
                },
                "operation": {
                  "enum": [
                    "search_symbols",
                    "lookup_symbols",
                    "find_references",
                    "goto_definition",
                    "get_document_symbols",
                    "get_diagnostics",
                    "get_hover",
                    "get_completions",
                    "pattern_search",
                    "generate_codebase_overview",
                    "search_codebase_map",
                    "rename_symbol",
                    "format",
                    "pattern_rewrite"
                  ],
                  "description": "The code intelligence operation to perform",
                  "type": "string"
                },
                "symbols": {
                  "description": "List of simple symbol names, not qualified (e.g. ['myFunction'] not ['MyClass.myFunction']). Required for lookup_symbols, max 10",
                  "items": {
                    "type": "string"
                  },
                  "type": "array"
                },
                "include_source": {
                  "description": "Include source code in results (optional for lookup_symbols)",
                  "type": "boolean"
                },
                "path": {
                  "description": "Directory path (optional, for generate_codebase_overview: workspace root, for search_codebase_map: path filter, for search_symbols: scope search to file or directory)",
                  "type": "string"
                },
                "file_path": {
                  "type": "string",
                  "description": "File path (required for rename_symbol/get_document_symbols/get_diagnostics/get_hover/get_completions, optional for format/pattern_rewrite/pattern_search/search_codebase_map)"
                }
              },
              "required": [
                "operation"
              ],
              "type": "object"
            }
          }
        }
